v.archives.arc.44381.4 Reel 4 of 4]\n* [https://archive.org/details/gov.archives.arc.24457 ''Invasion of Poland in 1939 by German Army''] (1943). Film Bulletin n. 48 US Department of the Army, Signal Corps Photographic Center. Internet Archive.\n* [https://archive.org/details/1939-09-04_Special_Release_Europe_At_War ''Special Release - Europe At War!''] (1939). Universal Studios. Internet Archive.\n\n{{World War II}}\n{{Polish wars and conflicts}}\n{{Nazi-Soviet relations}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Invasion Of Poland}}\n[[Category:Invasion of Poland| ]]\n[[Category:1939 in Poland]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1939]]\n[[Category:World War II invasions]]\n[[Category:Invasions of Poland]]\n[[Category:September 1939 events]]\n[[Category:October 1939 events]]\n", "name_user": "Deadlyaak", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(false information, This is fake information, so I deleted it because I don't want others to be misinformed.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Invasion_of_Poland"}
{"title_page": "Peter Zuckerman", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name        = Peter Edward Zuckerman\n| image       = \n| caption     = \n| office      = First Gentleman of Portland \n| term_label  = In role\n| term_start  = January 1, 2009\n| term_end    = December 31, 2012\n| predecessor = Karin Potter\n| successor   = Nancy Hales {{small|(First Lady)}}\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1979|12|27}}\n| birth_place = \n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = [[United States|American]]\n| other_names = \n| education   = [[Reed College]]\n| employer    =''[[The Oregonian]]''\n| title       = \n| religion    = \n| spouse      = \n| partner = [[Sam Adams (Oregon politician)|Sam Adams]]\n| children    = \n| parents     = \n| relatives   = \n| signature   = \n| website     = \n| known_for   = \n| occupation  =Journalist, Author, Activist\n| residence = [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]]\n}}\n'''Peter Zuckerman''' (born December 27, 1979) is an [[United States|American]] journalist and author who has focused his career in court reporting, [[investigative journalism]], and adventure stories. He is also a leader of several prominent progressive political campaigns.  \n\n==Early career==\nZuckerman attended [[Chadwick School]] in [[Los Angeles County, California]], and graduated from [[Reed College]] in Portland with a degree in [[biology]] in 2003.<ref>http://www.reed.edu/commencement/2003/grads.html</ref> While a student at Reed, Zuckerman served on the editorial board of the Reed College ''Quest'', a student-run newspaper. In March 2002 he wrote an opinion piece in ''The Oregonian'' (\"The drug Olympics\")<ref>{{cite news\n|title=In my opinion: The drug Olympics\n|first=Peter\n|last=Zuckerman\n|work=The Oregonian\n|date=March 1, 2002\n}}</ref> condemning competitive use of drugs like [[gamma-hydroxybutyric acid]], or GHB, at the school. He was the target of numerous threats within the Reed College community,<ref>{{cite news\n|title=IN MY OPINION: Voicing an opinion\n|first=Peter\n|last=Zuckerman\n|date=March 16, 2002\n|work=The Oregonian\n|url=http://infoweb.newsbank.com/iw-search/we/InfoWeb?p_action=doc&p_topdoc=1&p_docnum=1&p_sort=YMD_date:D&p_product=NewsBank&p_text_direct-0=document_id=(%200F25313B67CE3B77%20)&p_docid=0F25313B67CE3B77&p_theme=aggregated5&p_queryname=0F25313B67CE3B77&f_openurl=yes&p_nbid=R5BM4EJLMTIzNDcyMDcwMC4yMjU2NDc6MToxMzoxOTIuMjIwLjEyOC4w&&p_multi=ORGB\n}}</ref> and he was both adversely criticized and also praised in letters to the ''Oregonian''.<ref>{{cite news\n|title=Letter: Reed outraged by drug article\n|first=John\n|last=Saller\n|work=The Oregonian\n|date=March 9, 2002\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n|title=Letter: Peer pressure to excel\n|first=Andy\n|last=Bruno\n|work=The Oregonian\n|date=March 12, 2002\n}}</ref>\n\nZuckerman interned for the Portland weekly ''[[Just Out]]'' while at Reed, delivering the paper and fact-checking telephone numbers.<ref>[http://www.justout.com/news.aspx?id=41 Just Out Writers, from A (Acito) to Z (Zuckerman)] Just Out</ref> He also interned for the Portland bureau of the [[Associated Press]]<ref>http://web.reed.edu/career/calendar/2008/October/Where-the-Jobs-Are-Journalism.html</ref> and ''The Springfield News''. He went on to work as a journalist in Eastern Idaho.\n\n==Newspaper career==\nIn 2006, Zuckerman was the lead writer of a controversial multi-part story, ''Scouts' Honor'', in the [[Idaho Falls, Idaho|Idaho Falls]] ''[[The Post Register|Post Register]]'' about the coverup of a multi-state child molestation case involving at least two dozen minors and the [[Boy Scouts of America]] in Idaho.<ref name=\"postregister\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.postregister.com/scouts_honor |title=Scout's Honor |year=2005 |accessdate=2007-10-03 |periodical=[[The Post Register]] |postscript=<!--None-->}}</ref> He was accused of having a bias against the Boy Scouts of America and the LDS Church because of his sexual orientation.<ref name=\"Scouts Honor was a Disservice\">{{Cite news |title=Scouts Honor was a Disservice|date=May 24, 2005 |periodical=[[The Post Register]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Leave the Past Alone\">{{Cite news |title=Accused Bias|date=May 9, 2005 |work=[[The Post Register]]}}</ref>\n\nFor work on the series, Zuckerman received the 2006 [[Livingston Award]] and the 2007 [[C.B. Blethen Award]], and the Post-Register won the Scripps Foundation's 2005 [[National Journalism Awards]] for distinguished service to the [[First Amendment to the United States Constitution|First Amendment]].<ref name=\"livawards\">{{cite web |url=http://www.livawards.org/past/ |title=The Livingston Awards: Past Winners |accessdate=2007-10-03 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070928225730/http://www.livawards.org/past/ |archivedate = 2007-09-28}}</ref><ref name=\"seattletimes.nwsource.com\">{{cite news| url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/localnews/2003386137_blethens10m.html | work=The Seattle Times | title=Times, P-I take top honors in C.B. Blethen Awards | date=November 10, 2006}}</ref>\n\nAfter the story was published, Zuckerman became the target of personal attacks on the basis of his homosexual orientation.<ref name=\"Leave the Past Alone\" /><ref name=\"afterelton\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.afterelton.com/dennis/blog/PBS-airs-doc-on-gay-reporter |title=PBS airs documentary on gay Idaho Falls reporter |first=Dennis |last=Ayers |date=2007-09-14 |accessdate=2007-10-03 |periodical=[[AfterElton.com]] |postscript=<!--None-->}}</ref>\n\nZuckerman was profiled in a September 25, 2007, documentary, \"In A Small Town,\" broadcast in the [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]] series, [[Expos\u00e9: America's Investigative Reports]].<ref>https://www.pbs.org/wnet/expose/expose_2007/blog/peter_zuckerman/</ref> The documentary was a nominated for an [[Emmy Award]].<ref name=\"pbs\">{{Cite journal |title=In a Small Town (part 1) |url=https://www.pbs.org/wnet/expose/episode215/index.html |publisher=PBS |accessdate=2007-10-03 |format= &ndash; <sup>[https://scholar.google.co.uk/scholar?hl=en&lr=&q=intitle%3AIn+a+Small+Town+%28part+1%29&as_publication=&as_ylo=&as_yhi=&btnG=Search Scholar search]</sup> |postscript=<!--None--> |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071017112724/http://www.pbs.org/wnet/expose/episode215/index.html |archivedate = 2007-10-17}}</ref> A profile about Zuckerman in [[Harvard University]]'s [[Nieman Foundation for Journalism]] report about courage in journalism won the 2007 Mirror Award for best coverage of breaking news,<ref>http://www.mirrorawards.syr.edu/2007winners.html</ref> and he appeared on [[The Rachel Maddow Show (TV series)|The Rachel Maddow Show]].\n\nAfter moving back to Oregon, Zuckerman continued to investigate the Boy Scouts of America and the LDS church in his reporting in 2007 while working for ''[[The Oregonian]]''.<ref name=\"Men Sue Scouts, Mormon Church $25 million\">{{cite news | last =Zuckerman | first =Peter | authorlink =Peter Zuckerman | title =Men Sue Scouts, Mormon Church: $25 million - The six allege a former troop leader and church teacher abused them | newspaper =The Oregonian | date =October 4, 2007 | url =http://www.kellyclarkattorney.com/general/men-sue-scouts-mormon-church | accessdate =2009-02-05 | url-status =dead | archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20080821125516/http://www.kellyclarkattorney.com/general/men-sue-scouts-mormon-church/ | archivedate =August 21, 2008 }}</ref>   In this article, ''Men Sue Scouts, Mormon Church'', six men allege a former troop leader and church teacher abused them and seek $25 million in compensation as the LDS church failed to thoroughly investigate, report the abuse to law enforcement, provide mental health services to victims or remove the abuser from contact with children once it learned about the abuse.<ref name=\"Men Sue Scouts, Mormon Church $25 million\"/>\n\nZuckerman later changed his reporting to focus on stories that had more of an environmental bent. For example, he wrote about the [[United States Forest Service|Forest Service]] loosening its environmental standards so a gas corporation can clear cut through old growth in the [[Mount Hood National Forest]] to make way for an [[LNG]] pipeline.<ref>{{cite news\n|title=Forest Service plans to clear legal path for pipeline in Mount Hood forest\n|first= Peter\n|last=Zuckerman\n|work=The Oregonian\n|date=December 24, 2008\n|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/environment/index.ssf/2008/12/forest_service_plans_to_clear.html\n}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, Zuckerman and his journalism were the subject of a documentary that premiered at the [[Sundance Film Festival]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/video/church-and-the-fourth-estate-director-brian-knappenberger-sundance-documentary-interview/|title=\u2018Church And The Fourth Estate\u2019 Director Brian Knappenberger Shines A Light On Widespread Sexual Abuse Within Idaho Boy Scouts \u2014 Sundance Studio|last=Grobar|first=Matt|last2=Grobar|first2=Matt|date=2020-01-25|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> \n\n==Book career==\nIn January 2009, Zuckerman took a leave from ''[[The Oregonian]]'' to work on a \"dream book project\" after his partner, [[Sam Adams (Oregon politician)|Sam Adams]], was elected mayor of [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]] <ref>http://byronbeckwindow.ning.com/profiles/blogs/breaking-media-news-peter</ref> While researching the book, Zuckerman nearly died while traveling through remote regions of Nepal and ingesting a \"half plant, half animal\"<ref>https://www.scribd.com/doc/22565010/Finding-Nirvana-Peter-Zuckerman</ref> [[caterpillar fungus]].\n\nThe book, ''Buried in the Sky'', co-written with Amanda Padoan, tells the true adventure story of the [[2008 K2 disaster]] from the perspective of Sherpas and Pakistani high-altitude porters. The book was published on June 11, 2012 in the United States and Canada by [[W.W. Norton & Company]].<ref>[http://books.wwnorton.com/books/author.aspx?ID=23824]</ref> Reviews<ref>http://buriedinthesky.com/reviews/</ref> are positive.<ref>http://www.portlandmonthlymag.com/arts-and-entertainment/articles/peter-zuckerman-unlikely-adventures-june-2012</ref> Outside magazine described it as \"easily the most riveting and important mountaineering book of the past decade.\" ''The Wall Street Journal''<ref>{{cite news| title=Book Review: Buried in the Sky | last=Ybarra |first=Michael J. | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702303822204577466953130459274 | work=The Wall Street Journal|date=June 21, 2012|accessdate=December 5, 2016}}</ref> described it as \"enthralling.\" ''Men's Journal'' called it \"an indispensable addition to the genre,\"<ref>http://www.mensjournal.com/adventure/outdoor/the-sherpas-story-20120625</ref> and many publications, such as ''The Boston Globe'', favorably compared it to ''[[Into Thin Air]]''.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.boston.com/2012-06-10/arts/32095368_1_nepali-everest-ascent-sherpa-climbers | work=The Boston Globe | title=Learn more}}</ref> \n\nThe book was awarded the [[Orwell Award|2012 NCTE George Orwell Award]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ncte.org/library/NCTEFiles/Involved/Volunteer/Appointed%20Groups/Past_Recipients_Orwell_Award.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-06-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090326134658/http://www.ncte.org/library/NCTEFiles/Involved/Volunteer/Appointed%20Groups/Past_Recipients_Orwell_Award.pdf |archivedate=2009-03-26 }}</ref> the [[Banff Mountain Book Festival]] Award for mountain history,<ref>http://www.banffcentre.ca/mountainfestival/competitions/book/2012/#panel-6</ref> the [[National Outdoor Book Award]] for History.,<ref>http://www.noba-web.org/books12.htm</ref> the Independent Publishers Association award for general non-fiction,<ref>http://www.independentpublisher.com/article.php?page=1653</ref> and the American Society of Journalists and Author's Outstanding Book Award for general non-fiction.<ref>http://www.asja.org/for-writers/annual-writing-awards/2013winners.php</ref> \n\nIn 2019, Outside Magazine chose it as part of a \"Contemporary Adventure Canon\" made up of the best contemporary adventure books of all time.<ref>https://www.outsideonline.com/2397596/best-adventure-books-all-time</ref>\n\n==Teaching==\nZuckerman has received numerous journalism awards, including the [[Livingston Award]],<ref name=\"livawards\"/> the [[National Journalism Award]]<ref>http://www.pqmonthly.com/2012/06/local-author-peter-zuckerman-goes-to-worlds-edge-to-make-the-hidden-visible/</ref> and the [[C.B. Blethen Award]]<ref name=\"seattletimes.nwsource.com\"/>\n\nZuckerman has visited and taught at [[Poynter Institute]],<ref name=\"poynter\">{{cite web |url=http://www.poynteronline.org/profile/profile.asp?user=115111 |title=Peter E Zuckerman |accessdate=2007-10-03}}</ref> [[University of Georgia]]<ref>[http://www.uga.edu/news/artman/publish/071106_McGill_Fellows.shtml University of Georgia: News & Information<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> and the [[University of Southern California]].<ref>http://college.usc.edu/unruh/past_events/ and college.usc.edu/unruh/private/UnruhNews.pdf</ref> He is currently an adjunct fellow at the Attic Institute writing workshop<ref>http://atticwritersworkshop.com/teacher/peter-zuckerman</ref> and a resident at the Falcon Art Community.<ref>http://www.falconartcommunity.com/artists.html</ref>\n\n== Political campaigns ==\nIn 2013, Zuckerman became the press secretary for Oregon United for Marriage, the campaign to legalize same-sex marriage in Oregon,<ref name=\"Oregon United for Marriage\">[http://www.oregonunitedformarriage.org/or4msignaturedrivelaunch/]</ref> and for Oregon United Against Discrimination, a related campaign organized to defeat an anti-gay ballot measure.<ref>http://www.oregonlive.com/mapes/index.ssf/2014/05/gay_marriage_supporters_launch.html</ref> The anti-gay measure would have created an exception to Oregon's anti-discrimination law, allowing businesses to turn people away because of their sexual orientation or gender identity.<ref>http://www.advocate.com/oregon/2014/05/02/watch-oregons-first-ad-defeat-turn-away-gay-initiative</ref>\n\nDuring the marriage campaign, support for gay marriage increased by 14 points, volunteers collected 160,000 signatures to put gay marriage on the ballot, and the marriage campaign raised $3 million.<ref name=\"Reed College\">[http://www.reed.edu/news_center/posts/2014/how-reedies-helped-oregon-win-the-freedom-to-marry.html/]</ref> In May 2014, [[LGBT]] Oregonians won marriage early, through a court case.<ref>http://www.oregonlive.com/mapes/index.ssf/2014/05/oregon_gay_marriage_ban_struck.html</ref> The anti-gay ballot measure was prevented from qualifying for the ballot.<ref>http://www.oregonlive.com/mapes/index.ssf/2014/05/gay_marriage_backers_of_exempt.html</ref>\n\nLater that year, Zuckerman went on to become the communications director for New Approach Oregon / Yes on 91, the campaign to legalize recreational use of marijuana in Oregon ([[Oregon Ballot Measure 91 (2014)|Measure 91]]).<ref>http://www.newapproachoregon.com/contact/</ref><ref>http://www.bendbulletin.com/localstate/2283636-151/oregon-pot-campaign-raises-over-1-million</ref> [[Cannabis in Oregon|Marijuana legalization in Oregon]] passed with 56 percent of the vote, making Oregon the third state to legalize marijuana<ref>http://www.oregonlive.com/politics/index.ssf/2014/11/recreational_marijuana_passes.html</ref> \n\nIn 2016, Zuckerman directed communications for [[Oregon_Ballot_Measure_98_(2016)]], to provide more funding for education.<ref>https://www.statesmanjournal.com/get-access/?return=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.statesmanjournal.com%2Fstory%2Fnews%2Feducation%2F2016%2F10%2F14%2Fwhat-you-need-know-measure-98%2F91998580%2F</ref>  The initiative won with 65% of the vote. \n\nIn 2018, Zuckerman directed communications for a successful campaign to protect Oregon's sanctuary law (No on 105). <ref>https://kcfmradio.com/2018/10/31/28832/</ref> Measure 105 was defeated, 63% to 36%.<ref>https://ballotpedia.org/Oregon_Measure_105,_Repeal_Sanctuary_State_Law_Initiative_(2018)</ref>\n\nSince 2019, Zuckerman has been working as the campaign manager for the Drug Addiction Treatment and Decriminalization Initiative, which would decriminalize drug possession and expand access to treatment.<ref>https://www.oregonlive.com/politics/2019/12/signature-gathering-begins-for-oregon-initiative-to-decriminalize-small-amounts-of-all-drugs.html</ref><ref>https://ballotpedia.org/Oregon_Drug_Decriminalization_and_Addiction_Treatment_Initiative_(2020)</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nZuckerman is the son of Bruce Zuckerman, director of Archaeological Research at the [[University of Southern California]].<ref>http://college.usc.edu/faculty/faculty1003855.html</ref>{{dubious|date=December 2012}}\n\nZuckerman's partner is [[Sam Adams (Oregon politician)|Sam Adams]], the former mayor of Portland.<ref>[http://www.pointssouth.net/2003ps/staging/000249.htm Navigating Between Silence and Speech : Points South<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref name=wweek>{{cite news | url = http://wweek.com/editorial/3428/11010/ | title = Gossip should have no friends | date = 2008-05-21 | work = [[Willamette Week]] | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100112150932/http://www.wweek.com/editorial/3428/11010 | archivedate = 2010-01-12 }}</ref><ref>[http://miamiherald.typepad.com/gaysouthflorida/2008/12/gay-man-becomes.html Miami Herald]</ref> ''The Oregonian'' and Zuckerman took steps to ensure he had no influence over the coverage of his partner.<ref>[http://blog.oregonlive.com/oregonianeditors/2009/01/big_city_small_town.html Oregonian Editors Blog]</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Zuckerman put a Facebook Live video up about the cracking of an old safe his family had discovered under the floorboards. The video went viral, was picked up by media and got hundreds of thousands of views.<ref>https://www.patch.com/oregon/portland/amp/26477435/about-portland-forget-al-capones-vault-its-the-mystery-of-zuckerman-safe.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Orwell Award recipients}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zuckerman, Peter}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Portland, Oregon]]\n[[Category:LGBT writers from the United States]]\n[[Category:Reed College alumni]]\n[[Category:LGBT journalists from the United States]]\n[[Category:The Oregonian people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name        = Peter Edward Zuckerman\n| image       = \n| caption     = \n| office      = First Gentleman of Portland \n| term_label  = In role\n| term_start  = January 1, 2009\n| term_end    = December 31, 2012\n| predecessor = Karin Potter\n| successor   = Nancy Hales {{small|(First Lady)}}\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1979|12|27}}\n| birth_place = \n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = [[United States|American]]\n| other_names = \n| education   = [[Reed College]]\n| employer    =''[[The Oregonian]]''\n| title       = \n| religion    = \n| spouse      = \n| partner = [[Sam Adams (Oregon politician)|Sam Adams]]\n| children    = \n| parents     = \n| relatives   = \n| signature   = \n| website     = \n| known_for   = \n| occupation  =Journalist, Author, Activist\n| residence = [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]]\n}}\n'''Peter Zuckerman''' (born December 27, 1979) is an [[United States|American]] journalist and author who has focused his career in court reporting, [[investigative journalism]], and adventure stories. He is also a leader of several prominent progressive political campaigns.  \n\n==Early career==\nZuckerman attended [[Chadwick School]] in [[Los Angeles County, California]], and graduated from [[Reed College]] in Portland with a degree in [[biology]] in 2003.<ref>http://www.reed.edu/commencement/2003/grads.html</ref> While a student at Reed, Zuckerman served on the editorial board of the Reed College ''Quest'', a student-run newspaper. In March 2002 he wrote an opinion piece in ''The Oregonian'' (\"The drug Olympics\")<ref>{{cite news\n|title=In my opinion: The drug Olympics\n|first=Peter\n|last=Zuckerman\n|work=The Oregonian\n|date=March 1, 2002\n}}</ref> condemning competitive use of drugs like [[gamma-hydroxybutyric acid]], or GHB, at the school. He was the target of numerous threats within the Reed College community,<ref>{{cite news\n|title=IN MY OPINION: Voicing an opinion\n|first=Peter\n|last=Zuckerman\n|date=March 16, 2002\n|work=The Oregonian\n|url=http://infoweb.newsbank.com/iw-search/we/InfoWeb?p_action=doc&p_topdoc=1&p_docnum=1&p_sort=YMD_date:D&p_product=NewsBank&p_text_direct-0=document_id=(%200F25313B67CE3B77%20)&p_docid=0F25313B67CE3B77&p_theme=aggregated5&p_queryname=0F25313B67CE3B77&f_openurl=yes&p_nbid=R5BM4EJLMTIzNDcyMDcwMC4yMjU2NDc6MToxMzoxOTIuMjIwLjEyOC4w&&p_multi=ORGB\n}}</ref> and he was both adversely criticized and also praised in letters to the ''Oregonian''.<ref>{{cite news\n|title=Letter: Reed outraged by drug article\n|first=John\n|last=Saller\n|work=The Oregonian\n|date=March 9, 2002\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n|title=Letter: Peer pressure to excel\n|first=Andy\n|last=Bruno\n|work=The Oregonian\n|date=March 12, 2002\n}}</ref>\n\nZuckerman interned for the Portland weekly ''[[Just Out]]'' while at Reed, delivering the paper and fact-checking telephone numbers.<ref>[http://www.justout.com/news.aspx?id=41 Just Out Writers, from A (Acito) to Z (Zuckerman)] Just Out</ref> He also interned for the Portland bureau of the [[Associated Press]]<ref>http://web.reed.edu/career/calendar/2008/October/Where-the-Jobs-Are-Journalism.html</ref> and ''The Springfield News''. He went on to work as a journalist in Eastern Idaho.\n\n==Newspaper career==\nIn 2006, Zuckerman was the lead writer of a controversial multi-part story, ''Scouts' Honor'', in the [[Idaho Falls, Idaho|Idaho Falls]] ''[[The Post Register|Post Register]]'' about the coverup of a multi-state child molestation case involving at least two dozen minors and the [[Boy Scouts of America]] in Idaho.<ref name=\"postregister\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.postregister.com/scouts_honor |title=Scout's Honor |year=2005 |accessdate=2007-10-03 |periodical=[[The Post Register]] |postscript=<!--None-->}}</ref> He was accused of having a bias against the Boy Scouts of America and the LDS Church because of his sexual orientation.<ref name=\"Scouts Honor was a Disservice\">{{Cite news |title=Scouts Honor was a Disservice|date=May 24, 2005 |periodical=[[The Post Register]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Leave the Past Alone\">{{Cite news |title=Accused Bias|date=May 9, 2005 |work=[[The Post Register]]}}</ref>\n\nFor work on the series, Zuckerman received the 2006 [[Livingston Award]] and the 2007 [[C.B. Blethen Award]], and the Post-Register won the Scripps Foundation's 2005 [[National Journalism Awards]] for distinguished service to the [[First Amendment to the United States Constitution|First Amendment]].<ref name=\"livawards\">{{cite web |url=http://www.livawards.org/past/ |title=The Livingston Awards: Past Winners |accessdate=2007-10-03 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070928225730/http://www.livawards.org/past/ |archivedate = 2007-09-28}}</ref><ref name=\"seattletimes.nwsource.com\">{{cite news| url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/localnews/2003386137_blethens10m.html | work=The Seattle Times | title=Times, P-I take top honors in C.B. Blethen Awards | date=November 10, 2006}}</ref>\n\nAfter the story was published, Zuckerman became the target of personal attacks on the basis of his homosexual orientation.<ref name=\"Leave the Past Alone\" /><ref name=\"afterelton\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.afterelton.com/dennis/blog/PBS-airs-doc-on-gay-reporter |title=PBS airs documentary on gay Idaho Falls reporter |first=Dennis |last=Ayers |date=2007-09-14 |accessdate=2007-10-03 |periodical=[[AfterElton.com]] |postscript=<!--None-->}}</ref>\n\nZuckerman was profiled in a September 25, 2007, documentary, \"In A Small Town,\" broadcast in the [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]] series, [[Expos\u00e9: America's Investigative Reports]].<ref>https://www.pbs.org/wnet/expose/expose_2007/blog/peter_zuckerman/</ref> The documentary was a nominated for an [[Emmy Award]].<ref name=\"pbs\">{{Cite journal |title=In a Small Town (part 1) |url=https://www.pbs.org/wnet/expose/episode215/index.html |publisher=PBS |accessdate=2007-10-03 |format= &ndash; <sup>[https://scholar.google.co.uk/scholar?hl=en&lr=&q=intitle%3AIn+a+Small+Town+%28part+1%29&as_publication=&as_ylo=&as_yhi=&btnG=Search Scholar search]</sup> |postscript=<!--None--> |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071017112724/http://www.pbs.org/wnet/expose/episode215/index.html |archivedate = 2007-10-17}}</ref> A profile about Zuckerman in [[Harvard University]]'s [[Nieman Foundation for Journalism]] report about courage in journalism won the 2007 Mirror Award for best coverage of breaking news,<ref>http://www.mirrorawards.syr.edu/2007winners.html</ref> and he appeared on [[The Rachel Maddow Show (TV series)|The Rachel Maddow Show]].\n\nAfter moving back to Oregon, Zuckerman continued to investigate the Boy Scouts of America and the LDS church in his reporting in 2007 while working for ''[[The Oregonian]]''.<ref name=\"Men Sue Scouts, Mormon Church $25 million\">{{cite news | last =Zuckerman | first =Peter | authorlink =Peter Zuckerman | title =Men Sue Scouts, Mormon Church: $25 million - The six allege a former troop leader and church teacher abused them | newspaper =The Oregonian | date =October 4, 2007 | url =http://www.kellyclarkattorney.com/general/men-sue-scouts-mormon-church | accessdate =2009-02-05 | url-status =dead | archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20080821125516/http://www.kellyclarkattorney.com/general/men-sue-scouts-mormon-church/ | archivedate =August 21, 2008 }}</ref>   In this article, ''Men Sue Scouts, Mormon Church'', six men allege a former troop leader and church teacher abused them and seek $25 million in compensation as the LDS church failed to thoroughly investigate, report the abuse to law enforcement, provide mental health services to victims or remove the abuser from contact with children once it learned about the abuse.<ref name=\"Men Sue Scouts, Mormon Church $25 million\"/>\n\nZuckerman later changed his reporting to focus on stories that had more of an environmental bent. For example, he wrote about the [[United States Forest Service|Forest Service]] loosening its environmental standards so a gas corporation can clear cut through old growth in the [[Mount Hood National Forest]] to make way for an [[LNG]] pipeline.<ref>{{cite news\n|title=Forest Service plans to clear legal path for pipeline in Mount Hood forest\n|first= Peter\n|last=Zuckerman\n|work=The Oregonian\n|date=December 24, 2008\n|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/environment/index.ssf/2008/12/forest_service_plans_to_clear.html\n}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, Zuckerman and his journalism were the subject of a documentary that premiered at the [[Sundance Film Festival]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/video/church-and-the-fourth-estate-director-brian-knappenberger-sundance-documentary-interview/|title=\u2018Church And The Fourth Estate\u2019 Director Brian Knappenberger Shines A Light On Widespread Sexual Abuse Within Idaho Boy Scouts \u2014 Sundance Studio|last=Grobar|first=Matt|last2=Grobar|first2=Matt|date=2020-01-25|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> \n\n==Book career==\nIn January 2009, Zuckerman took a leave from ''[[The Oregonian]]'' to work on a \"dream book project\" after his partner, [[Sam Adams (Oregon politician)|Sam Adams]], was elected mayor of [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]] <ref>http://byronbeckwindow.ning.com/profiles/blogs/breaking-media-news-peter</ref> While researching the book, Zuckerman nearly died while traveling through remote regions of Nepal and ingesting a \"half plant, half animal\"<ref>https://www.scribd.com/doc/22565010/Finding-Nirvana-Peter-Zuckerman</ref> [[caterpillar fungus]].\n\nThe book, ''Buried in the Sky'', co-written with Amanda Padoan, tells the true adventure story of the [[2008 K2 disaster]] from the perspective of Sherpas and Pakistani high-altitude porters. The book was published on June 11, 2012 in the United States and Canada by [[W.W. Norton & Company]].<ref>[http://books.wwnorton.com/books/author.aspx?ID=23824]</ref> Reviews<ref>http://buriedinthesky.com/reviews/</ref> are positive.<ref>http://www.portlandmonthlymag.com/arts-and-entertainment/articles/peter-zuckerman-unlikely-adventures-june-2012</ref> Outside magazine described it as \"easily the most riveting and important mountaineering book of the past decade.\" ''The Wall Street Journal''<ref>{{cite news| title=Book Review: Buried in the Sky | last=Ybarra |first=Michael J. | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702303822204577466953130459274 | work=The Wall Street Journal|date=June 21, 2012|accessdate=December 5, 2016}}</ref> described it as \"enthralling.\" ''Men's Journal'' called it \"an indispensable addition to the genre,\"<ref>http://www.mensjournal.com/adventure/outdoor/the-sherpas-story-20120625</ref> and many publications, such as ''The Boston Globe'', favorably compared it to ''[[Into Thin Air]]''.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.boston.com/2012-06-10/arts/32095368_1_nepali-everest-ascent-sherpa-climbers | work=The Boston Globe | title=Learn more}}</ref> \n\nThe book was awarded the [[Orwell Award|2012 NCTE George Orwell Award]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ncte.org/library/NCTEFiles/Involved/Volunteer/Appointed%20Groups/Past_Recipients_Orwell_Award.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-06-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090326134658/http://www.ncte.org/library/NCTEFiles/Involved/Volunteer/Appointed%20Groups/Past_Recipients_Orwell_Award.pdf |archivedate=2009-03-26 }}</ref> the [[Banff Mountain Book Festival]] Award for mountain history,<ref>http://www.banffcentre.ca/mountainfestival/competitions/book/2012/#panel-6</ref> the [[National Outdoor Book Award]] for History.,<ref>http://www.noba-web.org/books12.htm</ref> the Independent Publishers Association award for general non-fiction,<ref>http://www.independentpublisher.com/article.php?page=1653</ref> and the American Society of Journalists and Author's Outstanding Book Award for general non-fiction.<ref>http://www.asja.org/for-writers/annual-writing-awards/2013winners.php</ref> In 2019, Outside Magazine chose it as one of the best adventure books of all time and part of the \"Contemporary Adventure Canon.\"<ref>https://www.outsideonline.com/2397596/best-adventure-books-all-time</ref>\n\n==Teaching==\nZuckerman has received numerous journalism awards, including the [[Livingston Award]],<ref name=\"livawards\"/> the [[National Journalism Award]]<ref>http://www.pqmonthly.com/2012/06/local-author-peter-zuckerman-goes-to-worlds-edge-to-make-the-hidden-visible/</ref> and the [[C.B. Blethen Award]]<ref name=\"seattletimes.nwsource.com\"/>\n\nZuckerman has visited and taught at [[Poynter Institute]],<ref name=\"poynter\">{{cite web |url=http://www.poynteronline.org/profile/profile.asp?user=115111 |title=Peter E Zuckerman |accessdate=2007-10-03}}</ref> [[University of Georgia]]<ref>[http://www.uga.edu/news/artman/publish/071106_McGill_Fellows.shtml University of Georgia: News & Information<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> and the [[University of Southern California]].<ref>http://college.usc.edu/unruh/past_events/ and college.usc.edu/unruh/private/UnruhNews.pdf</ref> He is currently an adjunct fellow at the Attic Institute writing workshop<ref>http://atticwritersworkshop.com/teacher/peter-zuckerman</ref> and a resident at the Falcon Art Community.<ref>http://www.falconartcommunity.com/artists.html</ref>\n\n== Political campaigns ==\nIn 2013, Zuckerman became the press secretary for Oregon United for Marriage, the campaign to legalize same-sex marriage in Oregon,<ref name=\"Oregon United for Marriage\">[http://www.oregonunitedformarriage.org/or4msignaturedrivelaunch/]</ref> and for Oregon United Against Discrimination, a related campaign organized to defeat an anti-gay ballot measure.<ref>http://www.oregonlive.com/mapes/index.ssf/2014/05/gay_marriage_supporters_launch.html</ref> The anti-gay measure would have created an exception to Oregon's anti-discrimination law, allowing businesses to turn people away because of their sexual orientation or gender identity.<ref>http://www.advocate.com/oregon/2014/05/02/watch-oregons-first-ad-defeat-turn-away-gay-initiative</ref>\n\nDuring the marriage campaign, support for gay marriage increased by 14 points, volunteers collected 160,000 signatures to put gay marriage on the ballot, and the marriage campaign raised $3 million.<ref name=\"Reed College\">[http://www.reed.edu/news_center/posts/2014/how-reedies-helped-oregon-win-the-freedom-to-marry.html/]</ref> In May 2014, [[LGBT]] Oregonians won marriage early, through a court case.<ref>http://www.oregonlive.com/mapes/index.ssf/2014/05/oregon_gay_marriage_ban_struck.html</ref> The anti-gay ballot measure was prevented from qualifying for the ballot.<ref>http://www.oregonlive.com/mapes/index.ssf/2014/05/gay_marriage_backers_of_exempt.html</ref>\n\nLater that year, Zuckerman went on to become the communications director for New Approach Oregon / Yes on 91, the campaign to legalize recreational use of marijuana in Oregon ([[Oregon Ballot Measure 91 (2014)|Measure 91]]).<ref>http://www.newapproachoregon.com/contact/</ref><ref>http://www.bendbulletin.com/localstate/2283636-151/oregon-pot-campaign-raises-over-1-million</ref> [[Cannabis in Oregon|Marijuana legalization in Oregon]] passed with 56 percent of the vote, making Oregon the third state to legalize marijuana<ref>http://www.oregonlive.com/politics/index.ssf/2014/11/recreational_marijuana_passes.html</ref> \n\nIn 2016, Zuckerman directed communications for [[Oregon_Ballot_Measure_98_(2016)]], to provide more funding for education.<ref>https://www.statesmanjournal.com/get-access/?return=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.statesmanjournal.com%2Fstory%2Fnews%2Feducation%2F2016%2F10%2F14%2Fwhat-you-need-know-measure-98%2F91998580%2F</ref>  The initiative won with 65% of the vote. \n\nIn 2018, Zuckerman directed communications for a successful campaign to protect Oregon's sanctuary law (No on 105). <ref>https://kcfmradio.com/2018/10/31/28832/</ref> Measure 105 was defeated, 63% to 36%.<ref>https://ballotpedia.org/Oregon_Measure_105,_Repeal_Sanctuary_State_Law_Initiative_(2018)</ref>\n\nSince 2019, Zuckerman has been working as the campaign manager for the Drug Addiction Treatment and Decriminalization Initiative, which would decriminalize drug possession and expand access to treatment.<ref>https://www.oregonlive.com/politics/2019/12/signature-gathering-begins-for-oregon-initiative-to-decriminalize-small-amounts-of-all-drugs.html</ref><ref>https://ballotpedia.org/Oregon_Drug_Decriminalization_and_Addiction_Treatment_Initiative_(2020)</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nZuckerman is the son of Bruce Zuckerman, director of Archaeological Research at the [[University of Southern California]].<ref>http://college.usc.edu/faculty/faculty1003855.html</ref>{{dubious|date=December 2012}}\n\nZuckerman's partner is [[Sam Adams (Oregon politician)|Sam Adams]], the former mayor of Portland.<ref>[http://www.pointssouth.net/2003ps/staging/000249.htm Navigating Between Silence and Speech : Points South<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref name=wweek>{{cite news | url = http://wweek.com/editorial/3428/11010/ | title = Gossip should have no friends | date = 2008-05-21 | work = [[Willamette Week]] | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100112150932/http://www.wweek.com/editorial/3428/11010 | archivedate = 2010-01-12 }}</ref><ref>[http://miamiherald.typepad.com/gaysouthflorida/2008/12/gay-man-becomes.html Miami Herald]</ref> ''The Oregonian'' and Zuckerman took steps to ensure he had no influence over the coverage of his partner.<ref>[http://blog.oregonlive.com/oregonianeditors/2009/01/big_city_small_town.html Oregonian Editors Blog]</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Zuckerman put a Facebook Live video up about the cracking of an old safe his family had discovered under the floorboards. The video went viral, was picked up by media and got hundreds of thousands of views.<ref>https://www.patch.com/oregon/portland/amp/26477435/about-portland-forget-al-capones-vault-its-the-mystery-of-zuckerman-safe.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Orwell Award recipients}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zuckerman, Peter}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Portland, Oregon]]\n[[Category:LGBT writers from the United States]]\n[[Category:Reed College alumni]]\n[[Category:LGBT journalists from the United States]]\n[[Category:The Oregonian people]]\n", "name_user": "AllenMendez", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peter_Zuckerman"}
{"title_page": "Jennie Pryce", "text_new": "Professor '''Jennie Elizabeth Pryce''' (born 1972) is a [[quantitative genetics|quantitative geneticist]] based in [[Melbourne]], [[Australia]]. Jennie is the [https://www.dairybio.com.au DairyBio] animal program leader in conjunction with her role as principal research scientist for [http://agriculture.vic.gov.au/ Agriculture Victoria] and Professor of animal genetics at [[La Trobe University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scholars.latrobe.edu.au/display/jpryce|title=Jennie Pryce|website=scholars.latrobe.edu.au|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nPryce was born in [[Shrewsbury]], [[Shropshire]], [[UK]] in 1972. She attended [[Shrewsbury High School (England)|Shrewsbury High School]] and then the [[Cheltenham Ladies College]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://shrewsburyhigh.gdst.net/newsletters/senior-newsletter-21/|title=Senior Newsletter|website=Shrewsbury High School|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\nPryce became inspired by genetics through owning and breeding her pedigree, registered herd of [[Holstein]] dairy cattle, under the prefix of Severnvale Holsteins and decided from a young age to pursue a career in genetics. In 1994 she received BSc (Hons) 1st class from the [[University of Edinburgh]], [[Scotland]] and a PhD in 1998 also from the University of Edinburgh in \"The Genetics of Health and Fertility of Dairy Cattle\" under the supervision of Professors Geoff Simm, [[William G. Hill]], Robin Thompson and Roel Veerkamp.<ref>Pryce, J. E., R. F. Veerkamp, R. Thompson, W. G. Hill, and G. Simm. \"Genetic aspects of common health disorders and measures of fertility in Holstein Friesian dairy cattle.\" Animal Science 65, no. 03 (1997): 353-360.</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nBetween 1998 and 2001 Pryce was a dairy geneticist with the [[Scotland's Rural College]], Edinburgh, Scotland. In 2001 she moved to New Zealand to take up a scientist position with the breeding company [[Livestock Improvement Corporation]]. Since 2008 Pryce has lived and worked in Melbourne, Australia where her main areas of research interest are genetic improvement of functional traits (especially dairy cow fertility and feed conversion efficiency), optimising breeding scheme design under [[genomic selection]] and development of dairy selection indices.<ref>{{cite web|title=Five ET heifers|url=http://www.dairyaustralia.com.au/Animal-management/Genetics/Comparing-cows/Five-ET-heifers.aspx|website=Dairy Australia|accessdate=15 August 2014}}</ref><ref>Pryce, J. E., M. D. Royal, P. C. Garnsworthy, and Ivan L. Mao. \"Fertility in the high-producing dairy cow.\" Livestock Production Science 86, no. 1 (2004): 125-135.</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pryce|first=J. E.|last2=Nguyen|first2=T. T. T.|last3=Axford|first3=M.|last4=Nieuwhof|first4=G.|last5=Shaffer|first5=M.|date=2018-04-01|title=Symposium review: Building a better cow\u2014The Australian experience and future perspectives1|url=https://www.journalofdairyscience.org/article/S0022-0302(18)30125-5/abstract|journal=Journal of Dairy Science|language=English|volume=101|issue=4|pages=3702\u20133713|doi=10.3168/jds.2017-13377|issn=0022-0302|pmid=29454697}}</ref>\n\nJennie is also a member of the International Committee for Animal Recording\u2019s Functional Traits Working Group and the Feed and Gas Working group<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dairybio.com.au/aboutus/|title=DairyBio \u00bb About Us|website=dairybio.com.au|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> and was also section editor of [[Journal of Dairy Science]], a member of the Functional Traits working group of the International Committee on Animal Recording (ICAR) and a member of the scientific committee of the World Congress on Genetics Applied to Livestock Production. In Australia, Pryce sits on the Dairy Moving Forward Fertility group and Holstein Australia's Breed Development and Conformation Committee.<ref>{{cite web|title=Breed Development and Conformation Committee|url=http://www.holstein.com.au/index.php/about-us/administration/breed-development-and-conformation-committee|publisher=The Holstein Friesian Association of Australia|accessdate=15 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\n\n\n\nIn 2016 Jennie was the first non-North American recipient of the prestigious American Dairy Science Association [https://www.adsa.org/About-ADSA/Awards J.L. Lush Award] for Animal Breeding and Genetics - established in 1982, the Award honours the memory of Dr J. L. Lush, who dedicated his life to advancing the field of animal breeding<ref>{{Cite journal|date=2016-12-01|title=Awards Program of the American Dairy Science Association\u00ae|url=https://www.journalofdairyscience.org/article/S0022-0302(16)30755-X/abstract|journal=Journal of Dairy Science|language=English|volume=99|issue=12|pages=10205\u201310223|doi=10.1016/S0022-0302(16)30765-2|issn=0022-0302}}</ref>. In 2019, Jennie was named as Australia\u2019s top researcher in the field of animal husbandry by research analytics firm League of Scholars; this award is based on number of citations for papers published in the top 20 journals in each field over the past 5 years. The winner must have done research work published in the 10 years immediately preceding the year of recognition, performed research in any area of animal breeding and genetics that had or has the potential for improvement of dairy cattle<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.farmonline.com.au/story/6453113/dairy-genetics-leader-rated-australias-best/|title=Dairy genetics leader rated Australia's best|date=2019-10-23|website=Farm Online|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>.\n\nThe 2018 Agriculture Victoria Awards category \u201cExcellence in Scientific Impact\u201d winner for [https://www.gardinerfoundation.com.au/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/GDF-ImProving-Herds-Fact-Sheet-FINAL11.pdf ImProving Herds]. ImProving Herds was an innovative and collaborative herd improvement research, development, extension and education project concluding in 2018. It was important because it spelt out the importance and role of herd improvement to dairy farmers and the broader dairy industry. It was significant because it quantified the economic importance of genetic improvement by comparing breeding indices to real economic farm data, which has only been done once before in the dairy sector. ImProving Herds culminated in one of Australia\u2019s largest on-farm dairy events, \u201cThe National Muster\u201d which was attended by over 300 farmers and advisors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dairybio.com.au/aboutus/|title=DairyBio \u00bb About Us|website=dairybio.com.au|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\nThe 2019 Agriculture Victoria Awards category \u201cExcellence in Scientific Impact\u201d winner for \u201cExcellence in Discovery and Invention\u201d for Classifying the fertility of dairy cows using mid-infrared spectroscopy Drs Phuong Ho, Tim Luke and Jennie Pryce from Genomic and Cellular Sciences have developed a model that can predict how likely a dairy cow is to conceive to first insemination with up to 77 per cent accuracy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dairybio.com.au/aboutus/|title=DairyBio \u00bb About Us|website=dairybio.com.au|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\nThe 2019 Agriculture Victoria Awards category \u201cExcellence in Leadership\u201d winner. This citation reads: \u201cProfessor Jennie Pryce is an outstanding nomination for the Leadership award category given the impact and dimensions of her leadership. She has provided outstanding and clear science leadership (scholarly and impact leadership), team leaderships, collaboration leadership nationally and international collaboration as well as industry translation and adoption. She is also an outstanding team, program and project leader and models agriculture values. Professor Pryce is highly skilled at communication and influence, and in clearly explaining complex science and evidence to academic peers and lay audiences. Jennie leads a major part of the most important innovation program for the Dairy Industry \u2013 DairyBio - making profitability improvements on farm. This innovation is critical to the dairy industry \u2013 regional Victoria\u2019s largest employer and a $1 billion export industry for the state. Professor Pryce has led development and delivering of successful research, worked to build industry groups\u2019 understanding and adoption, and led development of tools for direct benefit on farm by most farmers. Leading strong impact on the economy and society this year, Professor Pryce has been named Australia\u2019s top researcher in the field of animal husbandry by research analytics firm League of Scholars and published in The Australian\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dairybio.com.au/aboutus/|title=DairyBio \u00bb About Us|website=dairybio.com.au|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{GoogleScholar|id=Z5vvP9EAAAAJ|name=Jennie Pryce}}\n* {{youtube|id=D76rOWaan90|title=Presentation at the International Committee on Animal Recording}}\n* {{youtube|id=Yd8aF7UeVW0|title=More data, better breeding values - Dr. Jennie Pryce (DFCRC video)}}\n* {{youtube|id=US8292MuLQg|title=Improving feed efficiency - Dr Jennie Pryce (DFCRC video)}}\n*A long pedigree in genetics - https://dairybio.com.au/dairycattle/2019/11/27/a-long-pedigree-in-dairy-genetics/\n*[https://dairybio.com.au/dairycattle/2019/07/02/animal-improvement-update-with-dr-jennie-pryce/ Animal Genetic Improvement - Dr Jennie Pryce (Video)]\n*[https://dairybio.com.au/dairycattle/2019/07/02/word-congress-livestock-genetics-update-by-dr-jennie-pryce/ World Congress Livestock Genetics - update by Dr Jennie Pryce] (video)\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pryce, Jennie}}\n[[Category:Women geneticists]]\n[[Category:Australian women scientists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=August 2014}}\n\nProfessor '''Jennie Elizabeth Pryce''' (born 1972) is a [[quantitative genetics|quantitative geneticist]] based in [[Melbourne]], [[Australia]]. Jennie is the [https://www.dairybio.com.au DairyBio] animal program leader in conjunction with her role as principal research scientist for [http://agriculture.vic.gov.au/ Agriculture Victoria] and Professor of animal genetics at [[La Trobe University]].\n\n== Early life and education ==\nPryce was born in [[Shrewsbury]], [[Shropshire]], [[UK]] in 1972. She attended [[Shrewsbury High School (England)|Shrewsbury High School]] and then the [[Cheltenham Ladies College]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://shrewsburyhigh.gdst.net/newsletters/senior-newsletter-21/|title=Senior Newsletter|website=Shrewsbury High School|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\nPryce became inspired by genetics through owning and breeding her pedigree, registered herd of [[Holstein]] dairy cattle, under the prefix of Severnvale Holsteins and decided from a young age to pursue a career in genetics. In 1994 she received BSc (Hons) 1st class from the [[University of Edinburgh]], [[Scotland]] and a PhD in 1998 also from the University of Edinburgh in \"The Genetics of Health and Fertility of Dairy Cattle\" under the supervision of Professors Geoff Simm, [[William G. Hill]], Robin Thompson and Roel Veerkamp.<ref>Pryce, J. E., R. F. Veerkamp, R. Thompson, W. G. Hill, and G. Simm. \"Genetic aspects of common health disorders and measures of fertility in Holstein Friesian dairy cattle.\" Animal Science 65, no. 03 (1997): 353-360.</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nBetween 1998 and 2001 Pryce was a dairy geneticist with the [[Scotland's Rural College]], Edinburgh, Scotland. In 2001 she moved to New Zealand to take up a scientist position with the breeding company [[Livestock Improvement Corporation]]. Since 2008 Pryce has lived and worked in Melbourne, Australia where her main areas of research interest are genetic improvement of functional traits (especially dairy cow fertility and feed conversion efficiency), optimising breeding scheme design under [[genomic selection]] and development of dairy selection indices.<ref>{{cite web|title=Five ET heifers|url=http://www.dairyaustralia.com.au/Animal-management/Genetics/Comparing-cows/Five-ET-heifers.aspx|website=Dairy Australia|accessdate=15 August 2014}}</ref><ref>Pryce, J. E., M. D. Royal, P. C. Garnsworthy, and Ivan L. Mao. \"Fertility in the high-producing dairy cow.\" Livestock Production Science 86, no. 1 (2004): 125-135.</ref>\n\nPryce was also section editor of [[Journal of Dairy Science]], a member of the Functional Traits working group of the International Committee on Animal Recording (ICAR) and a member of the scientific committee of the World Congress on Genetics Applied to Livestock Production. In Australia, Pryce sits on the Dairy Moving Forward Fertility group and Holstein Australia's Breed Development and Conformation Committee.<ref>{{cite web|title=Breed Development and Conformation Committee|url=http://www.holstein.com.au/index.php/about-us/administration/breed-development-and-conformation-committee|publisher=The Holstein Friesian Association of Australia|accessdate=15 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\n\n\nThe 2016 recipient of the J.L. Lush Award for Animal Breeding and Genetics. This annual award recognises the research impact in the area of dairy genetics and is a competitive process. I was the first winner outside of North America and only the 2nd female in the history of the award. Established in 1982, the Award honours the memory of Dr J. L. Lush, who dedicated his life to advancing the field of animal breeding. The winner must have done research work published in the 10 years immediately preceding the year of recognition, performed research in any area of animal breeding and genetics that had or has the potential for improvement of dairy cattle.<ref>{{Cite journal|date=2016-12-01|title=Awards Program of the American Dairy Science Association\u00ae|url=https://www.journalofdairyscience.org/article/S0022-0302(16)30755-X/abstract|journal=Journal of Dairy Science|language=English|volume=99|issue=12|pages=10205\u201310223|doi=10.1016/S0022-0302(16)30765-2|issn=0022-0302}}</ref>\n\nJennie's research has achieved tangible practical results for the dairy industry, as illustrated by being used as a case study for the La Trobe University 2018 ARC Engagement and Impact assessment. The case study was awarded a rating of \u201cHigh\u201d for Impact and high for \u201cApproach to impact\u201d, meaning that the research, as per the ARC\u2019s definition, has been independently assessed as having had significant impact on \u2018the economy, society, environment or culture, beyond the contribution to academic research.\u2019 Additionally, the work contributed to the score of 5 in the ERA outcomes for Agriculture and Veterinary Sciences;\n\nThe 2018 Agriculture Victoria Awards category \u201cExcellence in Scientific Impact\u201d winner for [https://www.gardinerfoundation.com.au/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/GDF-ImProving-Herds-Fact-Sheet-FINAL11.pdf ImProving Herds]. ImProving Herds was an innovative and collaborative herd improvement research, development, extension and education project concluding in 2018. It was important because it spelt out the importance and role of herd improvement to dairy farmers and the broader dairy industry. It was significant because it quantified the economic importance of genetic improvement by comparing breeding indices to real economic farm data, which has only been done once before in the dairy sector. ImProving Herds culminated in one of Australia\u2019s largest on-farm dairy events, \u201cThe National Muster\u201d which was attended by over 300 farmers and advisors.\n\nAustralia\u2019s top researcher in the field of animal husbandry by research analytics firm League of Scholars and published in The Australian, based on number of citations for papers published in the top 20 journals in each field over the past 5 years (Google Scholar).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.farmonline.com.au/story/6453113/dairy-genetics-leader-rated-australias-best/|title=Dairy genetics leader rated Australia's best|date=2019-10-23|website=Farm Online|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\nThe 2019 Agriculture Victoria Awards category \u201cExcellence in Scientific Impact\u201d winner for \u201cExcellence in Discovery and Invention\u201d for Classifying the fertility of dairy cows using mid-infrared spectroscopy Drs Phuong Ho, Tim Luke and Jennie Pryce from Genomic and Cellular Sciences have developed a model that can predict how likely a dairy cow is to conceive to first insemination with up to 77 per cent accuracy.\n\nThe 2019 Agriculture Victoria Awards category \u201cExcellence in Leadership\u201d winner for \u201cExcellence in Discovery and Invention\u201d. This citation reads: \u201cProfessor Jennie Pryce is an outstanding nomination for the Leadership award category given the impact and dimensions of her leadership. She has provided outstanding and clear science leadership (scholarly and impact leadership), team leaderships, collaboration leadership nationally and international collaboration as well as industry translation and adoption. She is also an outstanding team, program and project leader and models agriculture values. Professor Pryce is highly skilled at communication and influence, and in clearly explaining complex science and evidence to academic peers and lay audiences. Jennie leads a major part of the most important innovation program for the Dairy Industry \u2013 DairyBio - making profitability improvements on farm. This innovation is critical to the dairy industry \u2013 regional Victoria\u2019s largest employer and a $1 billion export industry for the state. Professor Pryce has led development and delivering of successful research, worked to build industry groups\u2019 understanding and adoption, and led development of tools for direct benefit on farm by most farmers. Leading strong impact on the economy and society this year, Professor Pryce has been named Australia\u2019s top researcher in the field of animal husbandry by research analytics firm League of Scholars and published in The Australian.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{GoogleScholar|id=Z5vvP9EAAAAJ|name=Jennie Pryce}}\n* {{youtube|id=D76rOWaan90|title=Presentation at the International Committee on Animal Recording}}\n* {{youtube|id=Yd8aF7UeVW0|title=More data, better breeding values - Dr. Jennie Pryce (DFCRC video)}}\n* {{youtube|id=US8292MuLQg|title=Improving feed efficiency - Dr Jennie Pryce (DFCRC video)}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pryce, Jennie}}\n[[Category:Women geneticists]]\n[[Category:Australian women scientists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n", "name_user": "Cassheal", "label": "safe", "comment": "More citations and slight edits", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jennie_Pryce"}
{"title_page": "FC Slutsk", "text_new": "{{Infobox football club\n| clubname   = Slutsk\n| image      = Fc-slutsk-logo.png\n| fullname   = Athletic Football Club Slutsk<ref>{{cite web|title=\u041e\u0431\u0449\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u043e\u0431\u044a\u0435\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \"\u0421\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0438\u0432\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0444\u0443\u0442\u0431\u043e\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u043a\u043b\u0443\u0431 \"\u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a\"|url=http://sfc-slutsk.by/About|website=Sfc-slutsk.by|publisher=\u0421\u0424\u041a \"\u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a\"|accessdate=1 February 2016}}</ref>\n| nickname   = \n| shortname  = \n| founded    = 1998\n| dissolved  = \n| ground     = [[City Stadium (Slutsk)|City Stadium]], [[Slutsk]]\n| capacity   = 1,896\n| chrtitle   = Chairman\n| chairman   = Oleg Karanevsky\n| mgrtitle   = Head Coach\n| manager    = [[Vitaliy Pavlov (footballer, born 1965)|Vitaliy Pavlov]]\n| league     = [[Belarusian Premier League]]\n| season     = [[2019 Belarusian Premier League|2019]]\n| position   = 11th\n| website    = http://sfc-slutsk.by\n| pattern_la1 = _eastern18h\n| pattern_b1  = _eastern18h\n| pattern_ra1 = _eastern18h\n| pattern_sh1 = _adidaswhite\n| pattern_so1 = _3_stripes_white\n| leftarm1    = 0000FF\n| body1       = 0000FF\n| rightarm1   = 0000FF\n| shorts1     = 0000FF\n| socks1      = 0000FF\n| pattern_la2 = \n| pattern_b2  = _unterhaching1819t\n| pattern_ra2 = \n| pattern_sh2 = \n| pattern_so2 = \n| leftarm2    = FFFFFF\n| body2       = FFFFFF\n| rightarm2   = FFFFFF\n| shorts2     = FFFFFF\n| socks2      = FFFFFF\n}}\n\n'''FC Slutsk''' ({{lang-be|\u0424\u041a \u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a}}; {{lang-ru|\u0421\u0424\u041a \u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a}}) is a [[Belarus]]ian football club based in [[Slutsk]], [[Minsk Oblast]].\n\n==History==\nThe team was founded in 1998 as '''Slutsksakhar Slutsk'''. Between 1998 and 2007 they played in Minsk Oblast championship.\nIn 2008, they joined [[Belarusian Second League]]. In 2010, they finished in second place and were granted a promotion to [[Belarusian First League|First League]] in 2011. In early 2011 the team changed its name to '''Slutsk'''. \n\nDuring the [[2020 Belarusian Premier League]] season, Slutsk gained worldwide notoriety thanks to a [[Facebook]] group called FK Slutsk Worldwide.<ref name=\"\u0423 \u0431\u0435\u043b\u043e\u0440\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u00ab\u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a\u0430\u00bb \u0435\u0441\u0442\u044c \u0444\u0430\u043d-\u043a\u043b\u0443\u0431 \u0432 \u0410\u0432\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0438. \u0421\u043d\u0430\u0447\u0430\u043b\u0430 \u0432\u0441\u0435 \u0441\u043c\u0435\u044f\u043b\u0438\u0441\u044c \u043d\u0430\u0434 \u043d\u0430\u0437\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435\u043c, \u0430 \u0442\u0435\u043f\u0435\u0440\u044c \u043c\u0435\u0447\u0442\u0430\u044e\u0442 \u043a\u0443\u043f\u0438\u0442\u044c \u043c\u0435\u0440\u0447, \u0447\u0442\u043e\u0431\u044b \u043f\u043e\u043c\u043e\u0447\u044c \u0441 \u0434\u0435\u043d\u044c\u0433\u0430\u043c\u0438\">{{cite web |title=\u0423 \u0431\u0435\u043b\u043e\u0440\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u00ab\u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a\u0430\u00bb \u0435\u0441\u0442\u044c \u0444\u0430\u043d-\u043a\u043b\u0443\u0431 \u0432 \u0410\u0432\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0438. \u0421\u043d\u0430\u0447\u0430\u043b\u0430 \u0432\u0441\u0435 \u0441\u043c\u0435\u044f\u043b\u0438\u0441\u044c \u043d\u0430\u0434 \u043d\u0430\u0437\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435\u043c, \u0430 \u0442\u0435\u043f\u0435\u0440\u044c \u043c\u0435\u0447\u0442\u0430\u044e\u0442 \u043a\u0443\u043f\u0438\u0442\u044c \u043c\u0435\u0440\u0447, \u0447\u0442\u043e\u0431\u044b \u043f\u043e\u043c\u043e\u0447\u044c \u0441 \u0434\u0435\u043d\u044c\u0433\u0430\u043c\u0438 |url=https://www.sports.ru/tribuna/blogs/dyshite_glubzhe/2762554.html |website=sports.ru |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref> The group was initially founded by a group of Australians, however many people from around the world joined the group. The interest was initially founded because this was during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] and Belarus was one of the few nations that decided not to postpone or cancel their domestic league. Due to this, more people from around the world tuned in to see the league, and many began to root for Slutsk due to the name of the team being very similar to the derogatory [[English language|English]] word, [[Slut]]. During this season, Slutsk were suffering from financial difficulties and the fan group raised money to help the club.<ref name='\u0412 \u0410\u0432\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0438 \u0431\u043e\u043b\u0435\u044e\u0442 \u0437\u0430 \u0424\u041a \"\u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a\" \u0438 \u0441\u043e\u0431\u0438\u0440\u0430\u044e\u0442 \u0434\u043b\u044f \u043d\u0435\u0433\u043e \u0434\u0435\u043d\u044c\u0433\u0438'>{{cite web |title=\u0412 \u0410\u0432\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0438 \u0431\u043e\u043b\u0435\u044e\u0442 \u0437\u0430 \u0424\u041a \"\u0421\u043b\u0443\u0446\u043a\" \u0438 \u0441\u043e\u0431\u0438\u0440\u0430\u044e\u0442 \u0434\u043b\u044f \u043d\u0435\u0433\u043e \u0434\u0435\u043d\u044c\u0433\u0438 |url=https://euroradio.fm/ru/v-avstralii-boleyut-za-fk-sluck-i-sobirayut-dlya-nego-dengi |website=euroradio.fm |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref> As a thank you to the fans, the club displayed a banner at their stadium.<ref name=\"SFC Slutsk @ Facebook\">{{cite web |url=https://www.facebook.com/SFC.Slutsk.1998/posts/112691193730899 |website=SFC Slutsk @ Facebook |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Current squad==\n''As of March 2020 ''<ref>[http://sfc-slutsk.by/club/teams/main FC Slutsk squad]</ref>\n\n{{Fs start}}\n{{Fs player|no=4|name=[[Vitali Trubila]]|nat=BLR|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no=7|name=[[Yuriy Teterenko]]|nat=UKR|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no=8|name=[[Yegor Semenov]]|nat=BLR|pos=MF}}\n{{fs player|no=9|name=[[Artyom Serdyuk]]