{"title_page": "Mike Conley Jr.", "text_new": "{{short description|American basketball player}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Mike Conley Jr.\n| image = Mike Conley cropped 20131118 Clippers v Grizzles.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = Conley with the Grizzlies in 2013\n| position = [[Point guard]]\n| height_ft = 6\n| weight_lb = 175\n| league = [[National Basketball Association|NBA]]\n| team = Utah  Jazz\n| number = 10\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1987|10|11}}\n| birth_place = [[Fayetteville, Arkansas]]\n| nationality = American\n| high_school = [[Lawrence North High School|Lawrence North]]<br />([[Indianapolis, Indiana]])\n| college = [[Ohio State Buckeyes men's basketball|Ohio State]] (2006\u20132007)\n| draft_year = 2007\n| draft_round = 1\n| draft_pick = 4\n| draft_team = [[Memphis Grizzlies]]\n| career_start = 2007\n| career_end = \n| years1 = {{nbay|2007|start}}\u2013{{nbay|2018|end}}\n| team1 = [[Memphis Grizzlies]]\n| years2 = {{nbay|2019|start}}\u2013present\n| team2 = [[Utah Jazz]]\n| highlights = * [[NBA All-Defensive Second Team]] ({{nbay|2012|end}})\n* 3\u00d7 [[NBA Sportsmanship Award]] ({{nbay|2013|end}}, {{nbay|2015|end}}, {{nbay|2018|end}})\n* [[Twyman\u2013Stokes Teammate of the Year Award|NBA Teammate of the Year]] ({{nbay|2018|end}})\n* First-team All-[[Big Ten Conference|Big Ten]] (2007)\n* [[McDonald's All-American Game|McDonald's All-American]] ([[2006 McDonald's All-American Boys Game|2006]])\n* Third-team [[Parade All-America Boys Basketball Team|''Parade'' All-American]] (2006)\n| nba_profile = mike_conley\n| bbr = conlemi01\n}}\n'''Michael Alex Conley Jr.''' (born October 11, 1987) is an American professional [[basketball]] player for the [[Utah Jazz]] of the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA). He was a member of the [[Memphis Grizzlies]], the team who drafted him with the fourth overall pick in the [[2007 NBA draft]], before being traded in 2019 to the [[Utah Jazz]]. Conley is the son of [[Mike Conley Sr.]], an [[Olympic Games|Olympic]] gold and silver medalist in [[track and field]]. Conley is the Grizzlies' all-time leading scorer.\n\n==High school career==\nConley attended [[Lawrence North High School]] in [[Indianapolis]], where he led the basketball team to three consecutive state championships and an overall record of 103\u20137 in his four years as the starting point guard. Over his senior year, he dished out a total of 123 assists. He finished second in [[Indiana Mr. Basketball award|Indiana Mr. Basketball]] voting behind teammate [[Greg Oden]], who was the national player of the year. Among other accolades, Conley was selected to the [[McDonald's All American|McDonald's All American Team]] and named to the [[Parade All-America Boys Basketball Team|''Parade'' All-American]] Third Team.\n\nConsidered a five-star recruit by [[Rivals.com]], Conley was listed as the No. 3 point guard and the No. 18 player in the nation in 2006.<ref>[https://sports.yahoo.com/footballrecruiting/basketball/recruiting/player-Mike-Conley-22352;_ylt=AmhCplG4htbSlj_F4Z817eJGPZB4 Mike Conley Recruiting Profile]</ref> He committed to [[Ohio State University]] as one part of the number two recruiting class in the country that year, along with fellow [[Amateur Athletic Union|AAU]] teammates Greg Oden, [[Daequan Cook]], and [[Mark Titus]].\n\n==College career==\nIn his freshman year at Ohio State, Conley averaged 11.3 points and led the [[Big Ten Conference]] in [[Assist (basketball)|assists]] with 6.1 per game. Conley, together with fellow freshman star [[Greg Oden]], led the [[Ohio State Buckeyes|Buckeyes]] to a Big Ten conference championship and a runner-up finish in the [[NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Championship|NCAA Tournament]].<ref>[http://www.nba.com/playerfile/mike_conley/bio/ Mike Conley Stats, Video, Bio, Profile]</ref>\n\nOn the road to the championship game, the Buckeyes defeated [[Central Connecticut State Blue Devils men's basketball|Central Connecticut State]], [[Xavier University (Cincinnati)|Xavier]], [[University of Tennessee|Tennessee]], [[Memphis Tigers men's basketball|Memphis]], and [[Georgetown Hoyas men's basketball|Georgetown]], only to lose in the championship game to the repeat national champions [[Florida Gators men's basketball|Florida]]. Conley's best performance in the tournament came in the contest against [[Xavier University (Cincinnati)|Xavier]]. He recorded 21 points, 4 assists, 2 steals, and 3 blocks as Ohio State defeated the Musketeers in [[Overtime (sports)|overtime]]. Greg Oden fouled out in regulation, and Conley scored 11 of his 21 points in the extra period to lead the Buckeyes to a victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=274000034 |title=Xavier vs. Ohio State - Game Recap - March 17, 2007 - ESPN |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=2019-07-31}}</ref>\n\nEnding the season with totals of 441 points and 238 assists, Conley was named to the All-Big Ten First Team.\n\nFollowing his freshman season, Conley announced his intention to enter the [[2007 NBA draft]] along with Oden. He initially did not sign with an [[Sports agent|agent]] in order to preserve his eligibility to withdraw from the draft but ended up signing with his father several weeks before the draft.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nba/draft2007/news/story?id=2843539 |title=Source: Oden ends speculation, to declare for NBA |date=2007-04-20 |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=2019-07-31}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\n\n===Memphis Grizzlies (2007\u20132019)===\n\n====Early years (2007\u20132010)====\nConley joined fellow Buckeyes [[Greg Oden]] and [[Daequan Cook]] in declaring for the [[2007 NBA draft]]; both Conley and Oden were represented by Conley's father, whom the NBA certified as an agent earlier in the year. Conley was drafted by the [[Memphis Grizzlies]] as the fourth overall pick after Greg Oden, [[Kevin Durant]], and [[Al Horford]].\n\nConley had his first major appearances in January 2008. In Conley's first five career games, he scored 5, 10, 11, 11, and 15 points, respectively. He scored a season-high 20 points with 7 assists in a 134\u2013124 loss to the [[Cleveland Cavaliers]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/c/conlemi01/gamelog/2008/ |title=Mike Conley 2007-08 Game Log |website=Basketball-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=2019-07-31}}</ref> Conley finished his rookie year with averages of 9.4 points and 4.2 assists per game.\n\nConley started his sophomore campaign competing with [[Kyle Lowry]] for minutes. On January 25, 2009, the Grizzlies made [[Lionel Hollins]] the head coach after firing Mark Iavaroni. On February 19, 2009, Lowry was traded to the [[Houston Rockets]], which put Conley in the starting lineup. He averaged 10.8 points and 4.3 assists per game for the year.\n\nConley cemented his role as a full-time starter for the Grizzlies in 2009. He posted a season-high of 25 points on March 31, 2010, during a 102\u2013106 loss to the [[Dallas Mavericks]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/c/conlemi01/gamelog/2010/ |title=Mike Conley 2009-10 Game Log |website=Basketball-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=2019-07-31}}</ref> He averaged 12.0 points and 5.3 assists on the season.\n\n====2010\u201311 season====\nOn November 30, Conley put up a season-high 28 points in a 98\u201396 victory over the [[Los Angeles Lakers]]. Conley averaged 13.7 and 6.5 assists on the year to help the Grizzlies make the playoffs for the first time in five years. Entering with the eighth seed in the Western Conference, they were matched up in the first round with the top-seeded [[San Antonio Spurs]]. Conley and the Grizzlies went on to defeat the Spurs in six games and make NBA history as only the second eighth-seeded team to defeat a first seed in a seven-game series. They then lost to the [[Oklahoma City Thunder]] in the Semifinals after seven games.\n\n====2011\u201312 season====\nIn the shortened [[2011 NBA lockout|lockout season]], Conley played 62 of the Grizzlies' 66 games, during which he averaged 12.7 points and 6.5 assists. Conley and the Grizzlies would make the playoffs but fell in the first round to the [[Los Angeles Clippers]] in seven games.\n\n====2012\u201313 season====\nOn the year, Conley averaged 14.6 points, 6.1 assists, and 2.8 rebounds per game as the Grizzlies made the playoffs once again. They eliminated the [[Los Angeles Clippers]] and the [[Oklahoma City Thunder]] to reach the Western Conference Finals for the first time in franchise history. However, they then lost to the [[San Antonio Spurs]] in four games. It was in this season that Conley was named to the [[NBA All-Defensive Second Team]] for the first time.\n\n====2013\u201314 season====\n[[File:Mike Conley driving past Chris Paul 20131118 Clippers v Grizzles.jpg|250px|thumb|right|Conley driving past [[Chris Paul]] in a game in November 2013]]\nConley averaged a career-high 17.2 points, 6.0 assists, and 2.9 rebounds per game on the year as the Grizzles made the playoffs for the fourth consecutive season. They were then eliminated in the first round by the [[Oklahoma City Thunder]] in a seven game series. Conley was the recipient of the [[NBA Sportsmanship Award]].\n\n====2014\u201315 season====\nOn December 13, 2014, Conley scored a career-high 36 points to help the Grizzlies defeat the [[Philadelphia 76ers]], 120\u2013115, in overtime.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nj.com/sixers/2014/12/conleys_36_lead_grizzlies_past.html |title=Conley's 36 lead Grizzlies past 76ers in overtime, 120-115 |date=2014-12-14 |website=nj.com |language=en-US |access-date=2019-07-31}}</ref> The Grizzlies finished the season as the fifth seed in the Western Conference, making the playoffs once again. They then faced the [[Portland Trail Blazers]] in the first round and defeated them in five games. Near the end of Game Three of the series, Conley suffered a facial fracture, which forced him to miss the rest of the first round. He also missed Game One of the Semifinals against the [[Golden State Warriors]]. But Conley returned in Game Two of the series; and, while donning a protective mask, he scored 21 points to lead Memphis to a victory. However, Memphis eventually lost to the Warriors in six games.<ref>[https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/c/conlemi01/gamelog/2015/ Mike Conley 2014\u201315 Game Log]</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Conley received what would have been the first [[technical foul]] of his NBA career, but it was overturned by league officials the following day; {{as of|April 2017|lc=yes}}, he has yet to record a technical, having by far the longest streak without one of any NBA player.<ref name=\"techperf\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.wsj.com/amp/articles/mike-conley-the-nba-player-who-is-technically-perfect-1492090233 |title=The NBA Player Who Is Technically Perfect |last=Cohen |first=Ben |date=April 13, 2017 |work=[[Wall Street Journal]]}}</ref>\n\n====2015\u201316 season====\nOn October 31, 2015, Conley surpassed [[Shareef Abdur-Rahim]] (7,801) for third on the Grizzlies' career scoring list. He scored 22 points against the Brooklyn Nets to finish the game with 7,821 career points.<ref>[http://www.nba.com/games/20151031/BKNMEM/gameinfo.html Conley scores 22 points as Grizzlies defeat Nets 101\u201391]</ref> On January 18, 2016, Conley returned to the lineup after missing six games with a sore left Achilles and recorded his third double-double of the season with 15 points and 10 assists, helping the Grizzlies defeat the New Orleans Pelicans 101\u201399. Earlier that day, he was named one of the 30 finalists for the 2016 U.S. Olympic team.<ref>[http://www.nba.com/games/20160118/NOPMEM/gameinfo.html Gasol helps Memphis beat New Orleans 101\u201399]</ref> On March 12, he was ruled out for three to four weeks with a left foot injury.<ref>[http://www.nba.com/grizzlies/news/conley-anderson-update-160312 Mike Conley & Chris Anderson Update]</ref> He was later ruled out for the rest of the season on April 4 following a re-evaluation by team doctors, and hoping to return during playoffs.<ref>[http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/15136263/mike-conley-memphis-grizzlies-likely-done-season Sources: Mike Conley (Achilles) unlikely to return to Grizzlies lineup]</ref> The injury-riddled Grizzlies finished seventh in the Western Conference, and without Conley and [[Marc Gasol]], they were swept by the San Antonio Spurs in the first round of the playoffs. On April 23, Conley was awarded the NBA Sportsmanship Award for the second time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/grizzlies/news/conley-sportsmanship-award-160423|title=Mike Conley awarded 2015-16 NBA's Sportsmanship Award|work=NBA.com|date=April 23, 2016|accessdate=April 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\n====2016\u201317 season====\nOn July 14, 2016, Conley re-signed with the Grizzlies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/grizzlies/news/conley-singed-160714|title=Grizzlies re-sign Mike Conley to multi-year contract|work=NBA.com|date=July 14, 2016|accessdate=July 14, 2016}}</ref> His reported five-year, $153 million deal was the greatest contract by total value in NBA history at that point in time.<ref>{{cite web|last=Stein|first=Marc|url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/16684308/mike-conley-memphis-grizzlies-agree-principle-5-year-153-million-deal|title=Sources: Mike Conley, Grizzlies agree in principle on 5-year, $153 million deal|work=ESPN.com|date=July 2, 2016|accessdate=July 14, 2016}}</ref> On November 16, 2016, he scored 30 points and hit a career-high-tying seven three-pointers in a 111\u2013107 win over the [[Los Angeles Clippers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400899617|title=Grizzlies beat Clippers 111-107 on Gasol's late 3-pointer|work=ESPN.com|date=November 16, 2016|accessdate=November 17, 2016}}</ref> On November 29, he was ruled out for six to eight weeks with a fractured vertebrae.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wojnarowski|first=Adrian|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/sources-mike-conley-has-fracture-in-his-vertebrae-190316157.html|title=Sources: Mike Conley out 6 to 8 weeks with fractured vertebrae|work=Yahoo.com|date=November 29, 2016|accessdate=November 29, 2016}}</ref> He returned to action on December 16 after missing nine games. In the Grizzlies' 96\u201392 loss to the [[Sacramento Kings]], Conley passed [[Pau Gasol]] to become the all-time leading scorer in Grizzlies franchise history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400899836|title=Cousins, Koufos lead Kings to 96-92 win over Grizzlies|work=ESPN.com|date=December 16, 2016|accessdate=December 17, 2016}}</ref> On January 30, 2017, he scored a career-high 38 points in a 115\u201398 win over the [[Phoenix Suns]]. Conley matched his career best with seven three-pointers (in 10 attempts) and made 12 of 18 shots overall in his fourth 30-point game of the season\u2014he previously had just five over his entire career.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400900144|title=Conley scores career-high 38, Grizzlies rout Suns 115-96|work=ESPN.com|date=January 30, 2017|accessdate=January 31, 2017}}</ref> On February 15 against New Orleans, Conley passed [[Mike Miller (basketball player)|Mike Miller]] for the most three-pointers in franchise history with 845.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400900246 | title=Hill's 23 points, 18 from Davis lead Pelicans past Grizzlies | work=ESPN.com | date=February 15, 2017 | accessdate=February 16, 2017}}</ref> On March 29, he matched his career-high with seven three-pointers on his way to 36 points, helping the Grizzlies rout the [[Indiana Pacers]] 110\u201397.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400900511|title=Conley scores 36 as Grizzlies rout Pacers 110-97|work=ESPN.com|date=March 29, 2017|accessdate=March 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn April 22, 2017, Conley scored a franchise postseason record 35 points in a 110\u2013108 overtime win over the [[San Antonio Spurs]]. The win tied the first-round series at 2\u20132.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400950397|title=Tied at 2: Gasol lifts Grizzlies past Spurs 110-108 in OT|work=ESPN.com|date=April 22, 2017|accessdate=April 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====2017\u201318 season====\nConley appeared in 12 of the Grizzlies' first 13 games of the 2017\u201318 season before suffering a left Achilles injury.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/c/conlemi01/gamelog/2018/|title=Mike Conley 2017-18 Game Log|work=Basketball-Reference.com|accessdate=January 27, 2018}}</ref> On January 27, 2018, he was ruled out for the rest of the season after requiring surgery to smooth a small bone protrusion in his left heel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/grizzlies/news/medical-updates-180127|title=Grizzlies announce medical update for Conley, Parsons, Green and Ennis|work=NBA.com|date=January 27, 2018|accessdate=January 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2018\u201319 season====\nIn the Grizzlies' season opener on October 17, 2018, Conley made his first regular season appearance since November 2017 after missing 70 games in 2017\u201318. He played nearly 29 minutes, scored 11 points and had three assists and one steal in a 111\u201383 loss to the [[Indiana Pacers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401070695|title=Bogdanovic scores 19 points, Pacers rout Grizzlies 111-83|work=ESPN.com|date=October 17, 2018|accessdate=October 17, 2018}}</ref> On November 2, he scored a season-high 28 points in a 110\u2013100 win over the [[Utah Jazz]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401070803|title=Conley, Gasol help Grizzlies top short-handed Jazz 110-100|work=ESPN.com|date=November 2, 2018|accessdate=November 2, 2018}}</ref> On November 10, he set a new season-high with 32 points in a 112\u2013106 overtime win over the [[Philadelphia 76ers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401070860|title=Conley scored 32 points sending Grizzles past 76ers in OT|work=ESPN.com|date=November 10, 2018|accessdate=November 11, 2018}}</ref> On November 30, Conley improved his season-high scoring to 37 points and also made 10 assists in a 131\u2013125 double-overtime win over the [[Brooklyn Nets]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Conley carries Grizzlies past Nets 131-125 in 2OTs |url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401071004 |website=ESPN.com |accessdate=February 20, 2019 |date=November 30, 2018}}</ref> On March 5, 2019, after going scoreless in the first quarter, Conley scored 19 of his career-high 40 points in the fourth quarter of the Grizzlies' 120\u2013111 win over the [[Portland Trail Blazers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401071635|title=Conley's career-high sends Grizzlies past Portland 120-111|work=ESPN.com|date=March 5, 2019|accessdate=March 5, 2019}}</ref> On March 11, he was named Western Conference Player of the Week for games played from March 4 to March 10. It marked his first career Player of the Week award.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nba.com/grizzlies/news/mike-conley-named-nba-western-conference-player-of-the-week-190311|title=Mike Conley named NBA Western Conference Player of the Week|work=NBA.com|date=March 11, 2019|accessdate=March 12, 2019}}</ref> On March 27, in a 118\u2013103 loss to the [[Golden State Warriors]], Conley passed Marc Gasol to become the Grizzlies' all-time leader in career points.<ref>{{cite web |title=Curry, Durant each score 28 points, Warriors beat Grizzlies |url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401071791 |website=ESPN.com |accessdate=March 28, 2019 |date=March 27, 2019 |quote=Grizzlies: Conley's 3-pointer with 2:50 left in the second quarter moved him to first place on the franchise scoring list, passing former teammate Marc Gasol.}}</ref>\n\n===Utah Jazz (2019\u2013present)===\nOn July 6, 2019, the Grizzlies announced that they had traded Conley to the [[Utah Jazz]] in exchange for [[Grayson Allen]], [[Jae Crowder]], [[Kyle Korver]], the draft rights to [[Darius Bazley]], and a protected first round pick.<ref>{{cite web |title=Memphis Grizzlies acquire Grayson Allen, Jae Crowder, Kyle Korver, draft rights to Darius Bazley and future first round draft pick from Utah Jazz |url=https://www.nba.com/grizzlies/news/memphis-grizzlies-utah-jazz-trade-190706 |website=Memphis Grizzlies |publisher=NBA |accessdate=July 6, 2019 |language=en |date=July 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{NBA player statistics legend}}\n\n===NBA===\n====Regular season====\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|2007}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2007\u201308 Memphis Grizzlies season|Memphis]]\n| 53 || 46 || 26.1 || .428 || .330 || .732 || 2.6 || 4.2 || .8 || .0 || 9.4\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|2008}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2008\u201309 Memphis Grizzlies season|Memphis]]\n| '''82''' || 61 || 30.6 || .442 || .406 || .817 || 3.4 || 4.3 || 1.1 || .1 || 10.9\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|2009}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2009\u201310 Memphis Grizzlies season|Memphis]]\n| 80 || 80 || 32.1 || .445 || .387 || .743 || 2.4 || 5.3 || 1.4 || .2 || 12.0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|2010}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2010\u201311 Memphis Grizzlies season|Memphis]]\n| 81 || '''81''' || '''35.5''' || .444 || .369 || .733 || 3.0 || '''6.5''' || 1.8 || .2 || 13.7\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|2011}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2011\u201312 Memphis Grizzlies season|Memphis]]\n| 62 || 61 || 35.1 || .433 || .377 || '''.861''' || 2.5 || '''6.5''' || '''2.2''' || .2 || 12.7\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|2012}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2012\u201313 Memphis Grizzlies season|Memphis]]\n| 80 || 80 || 34.5 || .440 || .362 || .830 || 2.8 || 6.1 || 2.2 || '''.3''' || 14.6\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|2013}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2013\u201314 Memphis Grizzlies season|Memphis]]\n| 73 || 73 || 33.5 || .450 || .361 || .815 || 2.9 || 6.0 || 1.5 || .2 || 17.2\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|2014}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2014\u201315 Memphis Grizzlies season|Memphis]]\n| 70 || 70 || 31.8 || .446 || .386 || .859 || 3.0 || 5.4 || 1.3 || .2 || 15.8\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|2015}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2015\u201316 Memphis Grizzlies season|Memphis]]\n| 56 || 56 || 31.4 || .422 || .363 || .834 || 2.9 || 6.1 || 1.2 || '''.3''' || 15.3\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|2016}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2016\u201317 Memphis Grizzlies season|Memphis]]\n| 69 || 68 || 33.2 || '''.459''' || '''.407''' || .859 || '''3.5''' || 6.3 || 1.3 || '''.3''' || 20.5\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|2017}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2017\u201318 Memphis Grizzlies season|Memphis]]\n| 12 || 12 || 31.1 || .381 || .312 || .803 || 2.3 || 4.1 || 1.0 || '''.3''' || 17.1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|2018}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2018\u201319 Memphis Grizzlies season|Memphis]]\n| 70 || 70 || 33.5 || .438 || .364 || .845 || 3.4 || 6.4 || 1.3 || '''.3''' || '''21.1''' \n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=\"2\"|Career\n| 788 || 758 || 32.6 || .441 || .375 || .819 || 3.0 || 5.7 || 1.5 || .2 || 14.9\n{{s-end}}\n\n====Playoffs====\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2011 NBA playoffs|2011]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2010\u201311 Memphis Grizzlies season|Memphis]]\n| 13 || 13 || 39.0 || .388 || .297 || .830 || 3.8 || 6.4 || 1.1 || .2 || 15.2\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2012 NBA playoffs|2012]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2011\u201312 Memphis Grizzlies season|Memphis]]\n| 7 || 7 || '''39.6''' || .421 || '''.500''' || .750 || 3.3 || 7.1 || .9 || .0 || 14.1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2013 NBA playoffs|2013]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2012\u201313 Memphis Grizzlies season|Memphis]]\n| '''15''' || '''15''' || 38.3 || .384 || .281 || .763 || '''4.7''' || 7.1 || 1.7 || .3 || 17.0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2014 NBA playoffs|2014]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2013\u201314 Memphis Grizzlies season|Memphis]]\n| 7 || 7 || 38.1 || .431 || .111 || .769 || 4.6 || '''7.9''' || '''2.0''' || .1 || 15.9\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2015 NBA playoffs|2015]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2014\u201315 Memphis Grizzlies season|Memphis]]\n| 8 || 8 || 30.4 || .427 || .303 || .821 || 1.1 || 5.0 || 1.4 || .0 || 14.4\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2017 NBA playoffs|2017]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2016\u201317 Memphis Grizzlies season|Memphis]]\n| 6 || 6 || 37.3 || '''.485''' || .447 || '''.838''' || 3.3 || 7.0 || 1.7 || '''.5''' || '''24.7'''\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=\"2\"|Career\n| 56 || 56 || 37.4 || .414 || .317 || .792 || 3.7 || 6.7 || 1.4 || .2 || 16.5\n{{s-end}}\n\n===College===\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2006\u201307 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2006\u201307]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2006\u201307 Ohio State Buckeyes men's basketball team|Ohio State]]\n| 39 || 39 || 31.6 || .518 || .304 || .694 || 3.4 || 6.1 || 2.2 || .3 || 11.3\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=\"2\"|Career\n| 39 || 39 || 31.6 || .518 || .304 || .694 || 3.4 || 6.1 || 2.2 || .3 || 11.3\n{{s-end}}\n\n==Personal life==\nConley is a Christian. Conley has spoken about his faith saying, \"[Jesus] means the world. Jesus means everything.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Memphis Grizzlies point guard Conley lives for Jesus on, off basketball court|url=http://www.thealabamabaptist.org/print-edition-article-detail.php?id_art=26840&pricat_art=1|work=thealabamabaptist.org|date=March 7, 2013|accessdate=April 25, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140421095812/http://www.thealabamabaptist.org/print-edition-article-detail.php?id_art=26840&pricat_art=1|archivedate=April 21, 2014}}</ref>\n\nConley's father is [[Mike Conley Sr.]] who was the [[Olympic Games|Olympic]] gold and silver medalist in the [[triple jump]]. He is also the nephew of former [[American football]] linebacker [[Steve Conley]].\n\nOn July 5, 2014, Conley married his girlfriend Mary Peluso, whom he met at Ohio State.<ref>{{cite web|last=Nasrallah|first=Ramzy|url=http://www.elevenwarriors.com/ohio-state-basketball/2014/07/37225/mike-conley-got-married-yesterday|title=MIKE CONLEY GOT MARRIED YESTERDAY|work=elevenwarriors.com|date=July 6, 2014|accessdate=August 26, 2016}}</ref> In 2016, the couple welcomed their first child, Myles Alex Conley.<ref>{{cite web|last=Tillery|first=Ronald|url=http://www.commercialappeal.com/sports/grizzlies/marc-gasol-cleared-to-play-as-grizzlies-approach-training-camp-3c92c16e-84ce-6e61-e053-0100007f31bc-393728901.html|title=Marc Gasol cleared to play as Grizzlies approach training camp|work=commercialappeal.com|date=September 16, 2014|accessdate=September 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Sports}}\n* [[2006 high school boys basketball All-Americans]]\n* [[List of National Basketball Association franchise career scoring leaders]]\n*[[List of NBA players who have spent their entire career with one franchise]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20061025184721/http://ohiostatebuckeyes.cstv.com/sports/m-baskbl/mtt/conleyjr._mike01.html Ohio State Buckeyes bio]\n\n{{Utah Jazz current roster}}\n{{navboxes|list=\n{{2007 NBA Draft}}\n{{NBA Sportsmanship Award Winners}}\n{{Twyman\u2013Stokes Teammate Award}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Conley, Mike Jr.}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American basketball players]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Basketball players at the 2007 NCAA Men's Division I Final Four]]\n[[Category:Basketball players from Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Basketball players from Indiana]]\n[[Category:McDonald's High School All-Americans]]\n[[Category:Memphis Grizzlies draft picks]]\n[[Category:Memphis Grizzlies players]]\n[[Category:Ohio State Buckeyes men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Parade High School All-Americans (boys' basketball)]]\n[[Category:Point guards]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Fayetteville, Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Indianapolis]]\n[[Category:Utah Jazz players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American basketball player}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Mike Conley Jr.\n| image = Mike Conley cropped 20131118 Clippers v Grizzles.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = Conley with the Grizzlies in 2013\n| position = [[Point guard]]\n| height_ft = 6\n| weight_lb = 175\n| league = [[National Basketball Association|NBA]]\n| team = Utah  Jazz\n| number = 10\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1987|10|11}}\n| birth_place = [[Fayetteville, Arkansas]]\n| nationality = American\n| high_school = [[Lawrence North High School|Lawrence North]]<br />([[Indianapolis, Indiana]])\n| college = [[Ohio State Buckeyes men's basketball|Ohio State]] (2006\u20132007)\n| draft_year = 2007\n| draft_round = 1\n| draft_pick = 4\n| draft_team = [[Memphis Grizzlies]]\n| career_start = 2007\n| career_end = \n| years1 = {{nbay|2007|start}}\u2013{{nbay|2018|end}}\n| team1 = [[Memphis Grizzlies]]\n| years2 = {{nbay|2019|start}}\u2013present\n| team2 = [[Utah Jazz]]\n| highlights = * [[NBA All-Defensive Second Team]] ({{nbay|2012|end}})\n* 3\u00d7 [[NBA Sportsmanship Award]] ({{nbay|2013|end}}, {{nbay|2015|end}}, {{nbay|2018|end}})\n* [[Twyman\u2013Stokes Teammate of the Year Award|NBA Teammate of the Year]] ({{nbay|2018|end}})\n* First-team All-[[Big Ten Conference|Big Ten]] (2007)\n* [[McDonald's All-American Game|McDonald's All-American]] ([[2006 McDonald's All-American Boys Game|2006]])\n* Third-team [[Parade All-America Boys Basketball Team|''Parade'' All-American]] (2006)\n| nba_profile = mike_conley\n| bbr = conlemi01\n}}\n'''Michael Alex Conley Jr.''' (born October 11, 1987) is an American professional [[basketball]] player for the [[Utah Jazz]] of the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA). He was a member of the [[Memphis Grizzlies]], the team who drafted him with the fourth overall pick in the [[2007 NBA draft]], before being traded in 2019 to the [[Utah Jazz]]. Conley is the son of [[Mike Conley Sr.]], an [[Olympic Games|Olympic]] gold and silver medalist in [[track and field]]. Conley is the Grizzlies' all-time leading scorer.\n\n==High school career==\nConley attended [[Lawrence North High School]] in [[Indianapolis]], where he led the basketball team to three consecutive state championships and an overall record of 103\u20137 in his four years as the starting point guard. Over his senior year, he dished out a total of 123 assists. He finished second in [[Indiana Mr. Basketball award|Indiana Mr. Basketball]] voting behind teammate [[Greg Oden]], who was the national player of the year. Among other accolades, Conley was selected to the [[McDonald's All American|McDonald's All American Team]] and named to the [[Parade All-America Boys Basketball Team|''Parade'' All-American]] Third Team.\n\nConsidered a five-star recruit by [[Rivals.com]], Conley was listed as the No. 3 point guard and the No. 18 player in the nation in 2006.<ref>[https://sports.yahoo.com/footballrecruiting/basketball/recruiting/player-Mike-Conley-22352;_ylt=AmhCplG4htbSlj_F4Z817eJGPZB4 Mike Conley Recruiting Profile]</ref> He committed to [[Ohio State University]] as one part of the number two recruiting class in the country that year, along with fellow [[Amateur Athletic Union|AAU]] teammates Greg Oden, [[Daequan Cook]], and [[Mark Titus]].\n\n==College career==\nIn his freshman year at Ohio State, Conley averaged 11.3 points and led the [[Big Ten Conference]] in [[Assist (basketball)|assists]] with 6.1 per game. Conley, together with fellow freshman star [[Greg Oden]], led the [[Ohio State Buckeyes|Buckeyes]] to a Big Ten conference championship and a runner-up finish in the [[NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Championship|NCAA Tournament]].<ref>[http://www.nba.com/playerfile/mike_conley/bio/ Mike Conley Stats, Video, Bio, Profile]</ref>\n\nOn the road to the championship game, the Buckeyes defeated [[Central Connecticut State Blue Devils men's basketball|Central Connecticut State]], [[Xavier University (Cincinnati)|Xavier]], [[University of Tennessee|Tennessee]], [[Memphis Tigers men's basketball|Memphis]], and [[Georgetown Hoyas men's basketball|Georgetown]], only to lose in the championship game to the repeat national champions [[Florida Gators men's basketball|Florida]]. Conley's best performance in the tournament came in the contest against [[Xavier University (Cincinnati)|Xavier]]. He recorded 21 points, 4 assists, 2 steals, and 3 blocks as Ohio State defeated the Musketeers in [[Overtime (sports)|overtime]]. Greg Oden fouled out in regulation, and Conley scored 11 of his 21 points in the extra period to lead the Buckeyes to a victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=274000034 |title=Xavier vs. Ohio State - Game Recap - March 17, 2007 - ESPN |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=2019-07-31}}</ref>\n\nEnding the season with totals of 441 points and 238 assists, Conley was named to the All-Big Ten First Team.\n\nFollowing his freshman season, Conley announced his intention to enter the [[2007 NBA draft]] along with Oden. He initially did not sign with an [[Sports agent|agent]] in order to preserve his eligibility to withdraw from the draft but ended up signing with his father several weeks before the draft.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nba/draft2007/news/story?id=2843539 |title=Source: Oden ends speculation, to declare for NBA |date=2007-04-20 |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=2019-07-31}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\n\n===Memphis Grizzlies (2007\u20132019)===\n\n====Early years (2007\u20132010)====\nConley joined fellow Buckeyes [[Greg Oden]] and [[Daequan Cook]] in declaring for the [[2007 NBA draft]]; both Conley and Oden were represented by Conley's father, whom the NBA certified as an agent earlier in the year. Conley was drafted by the [[Memphis Grizzlies]] as the fourth overall pick after Greg Oden, [[Kevin Durant]], and [[Al Horford]].\n\nConley had his first major appearances in January 2008. In Conley's first five career games, he scored 5, 10, 11, 11, and 15 points, respectively. He scored a season-high 20 points with 7 assists in a 134\u2013124 loss to the [[Cleveland Cavaliers]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/c/conlemi01/gamelog/2008/ |title=Mike Conley 2007-08 Game Log |website=Basketball-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=2019-07-31}}</ref> Conley finished his rookie year with averages of 9.4 points and 4.2 assists per game.\n\nConley started his sophomore campaign competing with [[Kyle Lowry]] for minutes. On January 25, 2009, the Grizzlies made [[Lionel Hollins]] the head coach after firing Mark Iavaroni. On February 19, 2009, Lowry was traded to the [[Houston Rockets]], which put Conley in the starting lineup. He averaged 10.8 points and 4.3 assists per game for the year.\n\nConley cemented his role as a full-time starter for the Grizzlies in 2009. He posted a season-high of 25 points on March 31, 2010, during a 102\u2013106 loss to the [[Dallas Mavericks]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/c/conlemi01/gamelog/2010/ |title=Mike Conley 2009-10 Game Log |website=Basketball-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=2019-07-31}}</ref> He averaged 12.0 points and 5.3 assists on the season.\n\n====2010\u201311 season====\nOn November 30, Conley put up a season-high 28 points in a 98\u201396 victory over the [[Los Angeles Lakers]]. Conley averaged 13.7 and 6.5 assists on the year to help the Grizzlies make the playoffs for the first time in five years. Entering with the eighth seed in the Western Conference, they were matched up in the first round with the top-seeded [[San Antonio Spurs]]. Conley and the Grizzlies went on to defeat the Spurs in six games and make NBA history as only the second eighth-seeded team to defeat a first seed in a seven-game series. They then lost to the [[Oklahoma City Thunder]] in the Semifinals after seven games.\n\n====2011\u201312 season====\nIn the shortened [[2011 NBA lockout|lockout season]], Conley played 62 of the Grizzlies' 66 games, during which he averaged 12.7 points and 6.5 assists. Conley and the Grizzlies would make the playoffs but fell in the first round to the [[Los Angeles Clippers]] in seven games.\n\n====2012\u201313 season====\nOn the year, Conley averaged 14.6 points, 6.1 assists, and 2.8 rebounds per game as the Grizzlies made the playoffs once again. They eliminated the [[Los Angeles Clippers]] and the [[Oklahoma City Thunder]] to reach the Western Conference Finals for the first time in franchise history. However, they then lost to the [[San Antonio Spurs]] in four games. It was in this season that Conley was named to the [[NBA All-Defensive Second Team]] for the first time.\n\n====2013\u201314 season====\n[[File:Mike Conley driving past Chris Paul 20131118 Clippers v Grizzles.jpg|250px|thumb|right|Conley driving past [[Chris Paul]] in a game in November 2013]]\nConley averaged a career-high 17.2 points, 6.0 assists, and 2.9 rebounds per game on the year as the Grizzles made the playoffs for the fourth consecutive season. They were then eliminated in the first round by the [[Oklahoma City Thunder]] in a seven game series. Conley was the recipient of the [[NBA Sportsmanship Award]].\n\n====2014\u201315 season====\nOn December 13, 2014, Conley scored a career-high 36 points to help the Grizzlies defeat the [[Philadelphia 76ers]], 120\u2013115, in overtime.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nj.com/sixers/2014/12/conleys_36_lead_grizzlies_past.html |title=Conley's 36 lead Grizzlies past 76ers in overtime, 120-115 |date=2014-12-14 |website=nj.com |language=en-US |access-date=2019-07-31}}</ref> The Grizzlies finished the season as the fifth seed in the Western Conference, making the playoffs once again. They then faced the [[Portland Trail Blazers]] in the first round and defeated them in five games. Near the end of Game Three of the series, Conley suffered a facial fracture, which forced him to miss the rest of the first round. He also missed Game One of the Semifinals against the [[Golden State Warriors]]. But Conley returned in Game Two of the series; and, while donning a protective mask, he scored 21 points to lead Memphis to a victory. However, Memphis eventually lost to the Warriors in six games.<ref>[https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/c/conlemi01/gamelog/2015/ Mike Conley 2014\u201315 Game Log]</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Conley received what would have been the first [[technical foul]] of his NBA career, but it was overturned by league officials the following day; {{as of|April 2017|lc=yes}}, he has yet to record a technical, having by far the longest streak without one of any NBA player.<ref name=\"techperf\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.wsj.com/amp/articles/mike-conley-the-nba-player-who-is-technically-perfect-1492090233 |title=The NBA Player Who Is Technically Perfect |last=Cohen |first=Ben |date=April 13, 2017 |work=[[Wall Street Journal]]}}</ref>\n\n====2015\u201316 season====\nOn October 31, 2015, Conley surpassed [[Shareef Abdur-Rahim]] (7,801) for third on the Grizzlies' career scoring list. He scored 22 points against the Brooklyn Nets to finish the game with 7,821 career points.<ref>[http://www.nba.com/games/20151031/BKNMEM/gameinfo.html Conley scores 22 points as Grizzlies defeat Nets 101\u201391]</ref> On January 18, 2016, Conley returned to the lineup after missing six games with a sore left Achilles and recorded his third double-double of the season with 15 points and 10 assists, helping the Grizzlies defeat the New Orleans Pelicans 101\u201399. Earlier that day, he was named one of the 30 finalists for the 2016 U.S. Olympic team.<ref>[http://www.nba.com/games/20160118/NOPMEM/gameinfo.html Gasol helps Memphis beat New Orleans 101\u201399]</ref> On March 12, he was ruled out for three to four weeks with a left foot injury.<ref>[http://www.nba.com/grizzlies/news/conley-anderson-update-160312 Mike Conley & Chris Anderson Update]</ref> He was later ruled out for the rest of the season on April 4 following a re-evaluation by team doctors, and hoping to return during playoffs.<ref>[http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/15136263/mike-conley-memphis-grizzlies-likely-done-season Sources: Mike Conley (Achilles) unlikely to return to Grizzlies lineup]</ref> The injury-riddled Grizzlies finished seventh in the Western Conference, and without Conley and [[Marc Gasol]], they were swept by the San Antonio Spurs in the first round of the playoffs. On April 23, Conley was awarded the NBA Sportsmanship Award for the second time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/grizzlies/news/conley-sportsmanship-award-160423|title=Mike Conley awarded 2015-16 NBA's Sportsmanship Award|work=NBA.com|date=April 23, 2016|accessdate=April 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\n====2016\u201317 season====\nOn July 14, 2016, Conley re-signed with the Grizzlies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/grizzlies/news/conley-singed-160714|title=Grizzlies re-sign Mike Conley to multi-year contract|work=NBA.com|date=July 14, 2016|accessdate=July 14, 2016}}</ref> His reported five-year, $153 million deal was the greatest contract by total value in NBA history at that point in time.<ref>{{cite web|last=Stein|first=Marc|url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/16684308/mike-conley-memphis-grizzlies-agree-principle-5-year-153-million-deal|title=Sources: Mike Conley, Grizzlies agree in principle on 5-year, $153 million deal|work=ESPN.com|date=July 2, 2016|accessdate=July 14, 2016}}</ref> On November 16, 2016, he scored 30 points and hit a career-high-tying seven three-pointers in a 111\u2013107 win over the [[Los Angeles Clippers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400899617|title=Grizzlies beat Clippers 111-107 on Gasol's late 3-pointer|work=ESPN.com|date=November 16, 2016|accessdate=November 17, 2016}}</ref> On November 29, he was ruled out for six to eight weeks with a fractured vertebrae.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wojnarowski|first=Adrian|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/sources-mike-conley-has-fracture-in-his-vertebrae-190316157.html|title=Sources: Mike Conley out 6 to 8 weeks with fractured vertebrae|work=Yahoo.com|date=November 29, 2016|accessdate=November 29, 2016}}</ref> He returned to action on December 16 after missing nine games. In the Grizzlies' 96\u201392 loss to the [[Sacramento Kings]], Conley passed [[Pau Gasol]] to become the all-time leading scorer in Grizzlies franchise history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400899836|title=Cousins, Koufos lead Kings to 96-92 win over Grizzlies|work=ESPN.com|date=December 16, 2016|accessdate=December 17, 2016}}</ref> On January 30, 2017, he scored a career-high 38 points in a 115\u201398 win over the [[Phoenix Suns]]. Conley matched his career best with seven three-pointers (in 10 attempts) and made 12 of 18 shots overall in his fourth 30-point game of the season\u2014he previously had just five over his entire career.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400900144|title=Conley scores career-high 38, Grizzlies rout Suns 115-96|work=ESPN.com|date=January 30, 2017|accessdate=January 31, 2017}}</ref> On February 15 against New Orleans, Conley passed [[Mike Miller (basketball player)|Mike Miller]] for the most three-pointers in franchise history with 845.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400900246 | title=Hill's 23 points, 18 from Davis lead Pelicans past Grizzlies | work=ESPN.com | date=February 15, 2017 | accessdate=February 16, 2017}}</ref> On March 29, he matched his career-high with seven three-pointers on his way to 36 points, helping the Grizzlies rout the [[Indiana Pacers]] 110\u201397.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400900511|title=Conley scores 36 as Grizzlies rout Pacers 110-97|work=ESPN.com|date=March 29, 2017|accessdate=March 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn April 22, 2017, Conley scored a franchise postseason record 35 points in a 110\u2013108 overtime win over the [[San Antonio Spurs]]. The win tied the first-round series at 2\u20132.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400950397|title=Tied at 2: Gasol lifts Grizzlies past Spurs 110-108 in OT|work=ESPN.com|date=April 22, 2017|accessdate=April 23, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====2017\u201318 season====\nConley appeared in 12 of the Grizzlies' first 13 games of the 2017\u201318 season before suffering a left Achilles injury.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/c/conlemi01/gamelog/2018/|title=Mike Conley 2017-18 Game Log|work=Basketball-Reference.com|accessdate=January 27, 2018}}</ref> On January 27, 2018, he was ruled out for the rest of the season after requiring surgery to smooth a small bone protrusion in his left heel.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/grizzlies/news/medical-updates-180127|title=Grizzlies announce medical update for Conley, Parsons, Green and Ennis|work=NBA.com|date=January 27, 2018|accessdate=January 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2018\u201319 season====\nIn the Grizzlies' season opener on October 17, 2018, Conley made his first regular season appearance since November 2017 after missing 70 games in 2017\u201318. He played nearly 29 minutes, scored 11 points and had three assists and one steal in a 111\u201383 loss to the [[Indiana Pacers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401070695|title=Bogdanovic scores 19 points, Pacers rout Grizzlies 111-83|work=ESPN.com|date=October 17, 2018|accessdate=October 17, 2018}}</ref> On November 2, he scored a season-high 28 points in a 110\u2013100 win over the [[Utah Jazz]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401070803|title=Conley, Gasol help Grizzlies top short-handed Jazz 110-100|work=ESPN.com|date=November 2, 2018|accessdate=November 2, 2018}}</ref> On November 10, he set a new season-high with 32 points in a 112\u2013106 overtime win over the [[Philadelphia 76ers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401070860|title=Conley scored 32 points sending Grizzles past 76ers in OT|work=ESPN.com|date=November 10, 2018|accessdate=November 11, 2018}}</ref> On November 30, Conley improved his season-high scoring to 37 points and also made 10 assists in a 131\u2013125 double-overtime win over the [[Brooklyn Nets]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Conley carries Grizzlies past Nets 131-125 in 2OTs |url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401071004 |website=ESPN.com |accessdate=February 20, 2019 |date=November 30, 2018}}</ref> On March 5, 2019, after going scoreless in the first quarter, Conley scored 19 of his career-high 40 points in the fourth quarter of the Grizzlies' 120\u2013111 win over the [[Portland Trail Blazers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401071635|title=Conley's career-high sends Grizzlies past Portland 120-111|work=ESPN.com|date=March 5, 2019|accessdate=March 5, 2019}}</ref> On March 11, he was named Western Conference Player of the Week for games played from March 4 to March 10. It marked his first career Player of the Week award.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nba.com/grizzlies/news/mike-conley-named-nba-western-conference-player-of-the-week-190311|title=Mike Conley named NBA Western Conference Player of the Week|work=NBA.com|date=March 11, 2019|accessdate=March 12, 2019}}</ref> On March 27, in a 118\u2013103 loss to the [[Golden State Warriors]], Conley passed Marc Gasol to become the Grizzlies' all-time leader in career points.<ref>{{cite web |title=Curry, Durant each score 28 points, Warriors beat Grizzlies |url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401071791 |website=ESPN.com |accessdate=March 28, 2019 |date=March 27, 2019 |quote=Grizzlies: Conley's 3-pointer with 2:50 left in the second quarter moved him to first place on the franchise scoring list, passing former teammate Marc Gasol.}}</ref>\n\n===Utah Jazz (2019\u2013present)===\nOn July 6, 2019, the Grizzlies announced that they had traded Conley to the [[Utah Jazz]] in exchange for [[Grayson Allen]], [[Jae Crowder]], [[Kyle Korver]], the draft rights to [[Darius Bazley]], and a protected first round pick.<ref>{{cite web |title=Memphis Grizzlies acquire Grayson Allen, Jae Crowder, Kyle Korver, draft rights to Darius Bazley and future first round draft pick from Utah Jazz |url=https://www.nba.com/grizzlies/news/memphis-grizzlies-utah-jazz-trade-190706 |website=Memphis Grizzlies |publisher=NBA |accessdate=July 6, 2019 |language=en |date=July 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{NBA player statistics legend}}\n\n===NBA===\n====Regular season====\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|2007}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2007\u201308 Memphis Grizzlies season|Memphis]]\n| 53 || 46 || 26.1 || .428 || .330 || .732 || 2.6 || 4.2 || .8 || .0 || 9.4\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|2008}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2008\u201309 Memphis Grizzlies season|Memphis]]\n| '''82''' || 61 || 30.6 || .442 || .406 || .817 || 3.4 || 4.3 || 1.1 || .1 || 10.9\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|2009}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2009\u201310 Memphis Grizzlies season|Memphis]]\n| 80 || 80 || 32.1 || .445 || .387 || .743 || 2.4 || 5.3 || 1.4 || .2 || 12.0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|2010}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2010\u201311 Memphis Grizzlies season|Memphis]]\n| 81 || '''81''' || '''35.5''' || .444 || .369 || .733 || 3.0 || '''6.5''' || 1.8 || .2 || 13.7\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{nbay|201